The Higgs boson analysed
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson caused a certain stir last summer, and for good reason.
It is believed that this boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
And finally, it is the last particle whose existence has been predicted by the standard model - our best or least false" explanation of nature and the behavior of matter - but has not yet been observed empirically.
But for the physicists, it's not yet entirely certain that it's really the Higgs.
We know without the shadow of any doubt that we have a real new particle, and that it strongly resembles the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
Moreover, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented at a major physics congress in Kyoto this week, but data is still missing to be completely safe about it.
Nevertheless, let’s assume that it is actually the Higgs, because there seems to be a small risk of being mistaken, and let’s look at what it is about.
There is an inevitably inevitable law in this world, which means that two objects cannot be present simultaneously in the same place.
It's not possible to violate this rule - and don't try too hard as you'll hurt yourself.
For even if particle physics is a really strange world, it turns out that such a law also applies to it: the Paulian exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state," whereby this "state" consists broadly of some of its properties.
Based on this, the physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In one corner are the good citizens, who are called Fermione and like to obey the Pauli principle.
And in the other, the bosons move, a foul band of anarchists to whom nothing is sacred - in any case not this principle, which means that they can indeed be in the same place at the same time.
According to the website The Particle Adventure of the Berkeley Laboratories (which, by the way, is absolutely amazing) are divided into two groups: the mesons, which we will not treat here and the "power particles" through which the great forces of nature spread and with which the Higgs boson would somehow be related.
However, it must be emphasized here that these bosons are not all such exotic creatures as you might think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, then only thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon or the "light particle," which is the "messenger" of electromagnetic power.
Namely, if a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, the electromagnetic field is "disturbed" at exactly that location, roughly like a pebble that has been thrown into a pond.
This “disturbance” creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon and thus one of the bosons “carriers of force”.
More stable field
The same goes for the Higgs boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, must be "disturbed" for this boson to show.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the pathogen must reach very high energies, a little comparable to a frozen pond whose surface could only be furrowed by a very large rock.
Therefore, a huge particle accelerator such as the CERN is required - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring with a circumference of 27 km! - to achieve such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again helpful to explain the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
It is, in fact, not all the particles and not all materials that interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do this, but others do not - for example, a sheet of paper would never hold on to the fridge by itself.
And equally, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those who do it possess a mass, while the others (like the photon, by the way) do not have mass.
What can all this research now be "good," Ms. Plamondon asks?
For science, they serve to review the standard model (SM), and they also allow physicists to closely examine all the discrepancies between the observations and the predictions of the SM.
There are, by the way, numerous physicists who longingly hope that such deviations will be found, since the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and stuff some holes of the model.
It must be said that the latter still has great deficiencies, since it does not provide an explanation for gravity (ups!) and the dark matter, which is approx. 80% of the matter of the universe (again ups!).
However, such deviations have not been found at CERN until now.
Impact
The impact of this research on the general population is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there would be none.
By the way: in the early 60s, the pioneers of the laser in the Bell laboratories did not suspect that their work would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle - who worked at the Bell Labs where the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who developed the first continuous wave laser himself in 1962 - has already told us that the laser was viewed rather than a "laboratory gimmick" in the beginning.
Imagine...
In addition, applications can also result from all the instruments that surround the research.
For example, Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor in 1969 during his work in optics.
Although it was not the original purpose, this sensor now serves as an "eye" to all digital cameras worldwide and earned it the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
Of course, this doesn't mean that the LHC's activities will inevitably change our lives, but it means you really can never know...
