In fact, the Bitcoin invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym) is both a virtual currency (but convertible into dollars, euros, etc.) and a protocol for secure exchanges such as BitTorrent, which allows the direct exchange of files.
With 15,000 computers on the network, about 200,000 transactions have already been recorded.
A few thousand websites accept Bitcoin as a donation or as a means of payment.
After the price of Bitcoin reached a peak of 30 dollars (23 euros) in June 2011, it fell to 2 dollars five months later, before recovering to around ten dollars today (the prices are listed on the website bitcoincharts.com).
Nothing particularly impressive compared to world trade in real currencies or financial products.
Nevertheless, the European Central Bank (ECB) has shown interest in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
She describes Bitcoin as “the virtual currency with the greatest success,” “in competition with the dollar or euro,” and “similar to traditional currencies.”
Bitcoin is different from other types of virtual currencies such as the “credits” that are used to advance in a video game that you can win or buy (and sometimes back) by playing.
The social network Facebook has also developed such a system.
However, trade is controlled and processed each time by a central authority.
With Bitcoin, all network nodes are simultaneously the depository of the invoice book, auditors, money issuers, as well as buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
In reality, every transaction between two users takes place between two email addresses in the form of an email.
With the difference that the user can choose a different address for each payment, which ensures anonymity.
A number of the data related to this transaction is signed electronically by a double encryption system.
This allows the network to check the authenticity of the transaction.
With the help of the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the traded bitcoins are present in the public account book distributed throughout the network.
The key step is to enter this new transaction into this book.
This is done via a mathematical task that is started on the computers, with the winner who is a kind of provisional central banker having the privilege of adding this extra line.
It is a dismemberment of the file, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a shorter and unique electronic fingerprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before the whole thing is "chopped up."
The goal is to find the number that yields a special fingerprint (many zeros at the beginning).
When this number has been found, the other nodes can effortlessly check if it is the correct one.
The transaction is thus permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions, and any modification would change the fingerprint.
If a user wants to pay for cheating twice very quickly (less than 10 minutes) with the same money, only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network and the other would remain without linking, since both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the task receives 50 bitcoins.
To prevent inflation, this reward is regularly halved, probably before the end of 2012.
The bitcoins in circulation are thus limited to 21 million, but are divisible to a hundred millionth, which leaves some room for manoeuvre.
In addition, the difficulty of the task is increased with each improvement in computing power.
The life of the network has already had ups and downs.
The websites that provide services for Bitcoin have been attacked and the bitcoin deposits stolen.
"The vulnerability used does not affect the actual protocol," assures Pierre Noizat, who has just introduced Paymium, which is a company for paying with real money and uses the network Bitcoin.
The ECB also reports on the possibilities of money laundering through this anonymous service.
However, cash also has these shortcomings.
Important players such as Wikipedia refuse to make donations of this kind.
They are accepted by others like the blog platform WordPress.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the accounting book, showing that almost 80% of Bitcoins are out of circulation.
A "mega-final sale" was launched in November.
"Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged," rejoices Jon Holmquist, who works for the company Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of a book about this currency, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as a transaction network.
Its system Paytunia corresponds to a credit card (with real money) or a contactless payment with a mobile phone, but uses Bitcoin to validate the transactions, which are thereby cheaper.
In addition, the owner manages his identity and can therefore remain anonymous.
The system can be easily implemented at dealers, and the latter do not need to install new terminals or computer programs.
You simply need to provide an address that can be "photographed and recognized" by a phone, Pierre Noizat states, who assures that he has thousands of users.
There is a general trend in which hierarchical systems are being reconsidered in favour of more horizontal systems.
“It will take some time for Bitcoin to prevail, but 2013 could be a turning point,” he predicts.
By the way, the ECB’s report envisages reassessing the various risks that are now considered to be high in the event of the success of this currency.
