A Constitution with the Crowbar in Egypt
This is a new poker game by President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever in terms of the constitutional declaration, which temporarily grants it unlimited power of attorney, he has decided to put everything on a map.
To everyone's surprise, he announced on Wednesday that the constituent assembly would pass its final version the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of state had granted this plenary two additional months for the completion of his work.
Egypt has now been relying on a provisional, multi-amplified text for almost two years, which weakens institutional stability and leads to a legal mess.
This new initiative has only made for an even greater division of the country.
For his opponents, the president persists in his "autocratic delirium" by continuing to "break his word" and "trespassing the right underfoot."
On the part of its proponents, it is assured that it is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as soon as possible and to speed up the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 14 days.
A very short period of time, which forces the brothers to refrain from their intention to explain the text section to the Egyptians.
For the president, it is also a way to find his public and democratic legitimacy again while the protest is raging across the country.
After reaffirmations in an interview with the American newsree, Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote benevolent.
Especially since the Egyptian people are given an ultimatum with this resort to a hasty vote: "Either you vote for my draft or I retain the unlimited power of attorney", the latter should supposedly come to an end after the adoption of the constitution.
85 mostly Islamist members of this Constituent Assembly passed the text yesterday in a strange atmosphere.
The majority of liberals have not complied with the call.
Shortly before the Constitutional Declaration in mid-November, they turned away, as they believe that they have not been able to bring out their viewpoints.
Representatives of human rights organisations, religious minorities or civil society have acted equally.
In order to achieve quorum, 11 people, deputy members, were added in a hurry yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Not surprisingly, the articles were mostly passed unanimously.
The commentators, by the way, found it entertaining that the only disagreement of the day... was expressed in the time for prayer, since some members of the panel were of the opinion that the commute clock of the Constituent Assembly did not exactly.
The text, which was adopted last night, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, which attracted all attention, ultimately remains identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, and states that "the principles of Sharia are the main source of law."
The Salafist parties, for which the establishment of Islamic law is an important demand, had the hope of replacing "the principles" with "the rules," which would have made stricter application possible.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been changed is a testament to their goodwill and to their respect for the other members of Egyptian society.
"Shinesity" is reciprocated by the liberals, who see this only as a propaganda blow.
Because, according to them, the Islamization of the constitution takes place via other articles.
In particular, they have in mind Article 220, which grants the University of Al-Azhar an advisory role, in particular with regard to the verification of conformity with the laws of Sharia law.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, this is disturbing, since "the persons who are asked to comment have not been elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
You can see in this the first signs of a theocracy.”
Liberals' fears are also fueled by the fact that the next rector of this university is likely to be far less moderate than the present one.
“Currently, there is no concrete religious commitment.
With this constitution, we remain within the framework of the bourgeois state.
Most of the lawyers who have worked on this text are not Ulema, but academics who have been trained in part in the French system," appeases Alexis Blouet, who writes a doctoral thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
However, he acknowledges that "there may be ambiguity in relation to Article 220, since the terms used are borrowed from the religious vocabulary.
One refers in particular to the "Fiqh" [Islamic case law, note d. Red.].
And in the future, the question could be raised to what extent civil judges are competent to decide on it."
In addition to its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is strongly criticized for the far-reaching powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argues that these are significantly reduced compared to the former regime.
Another point of contention: the powers of the army.
In line with the military's wish, the examination of the defence budget is not submitted to Parliament, but to a national defence council.
Likewise, there will be no ban on civil proceedings in military courts, as the associations for the defence of human rights have demanded.
The latter also share their fears regarding the text, which they consider to be threatening to be freedom.
The fact of blasphemy is being maintained, and insults are now banned, which could have serious consequences for the right to freedom of expression, especially for the press.
In addition, no more article refers to the protection of women, emphasizes Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
In their opinion, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture by Article 36.
This word was not included in the previous Constitution.
While the Egyptian president had to speak on television last night, demonstrations are planned for this afternoon.
The head of state's proponents will march Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists expect holy sites, the world's navel and a sea of brine
The Promised Land unites in itself the glory of biblical truths, modern comfort and an untouched nature.
AIF will give you the top five reasons for visiting Israel.
Bow before the holy sites
Visit the river Jordan where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that all those who bathe in this river receive God's blessings.
Galilee is the place where Jesus performed his miracles: the transformation of water into wine at a wedding celebration, walking on the water, the cessation of the sea tower and fishing.
This is where Jesus appeared to his disciples after the resurrection.
Most of the sanctuaries are found in Jerusalem.
Believers celebrate the path of suffering here or The Way of the Cross of Jesus Christ (in Latin: Via Dolorosa).
The trail begins at the Roman fortress of Antonia, Pretorium, where the court was, and leads through the streets of the old town to the Church of the Holy Sepulchre on Mount Golgotha, where the crucifixion site, the anointing stone and the tomb of Jesus are located.
Here, according to the Christian conception, is the navel of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of humanity.
The monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem stands in the place where, according to a Christian legend, the tree grew from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus.
In Jerusalem is also the most sacred place of the Jews - the Western Wall, the remains of a temple, which of the Romans in the year 70 n. Chr. was destroyed.
Traditionally, people of different faiths leave notes with wishes, which then come true.
Take a trip up
The ruins of the fortress Massada form the remains of the secret hideout from enemies, the Herod the Great in the year 25 n. Chr. had built for his family.
They are located on a rock face in the mountains at 450 meters above sea level.
Only mountaineers can reach the ruins on their own.
Everyone else brings a cable car to this historic summit.
In the north of the country at an altitude of 1600 to 2040 meters is the famous ski resort Hermon, where countless tourists are drawn during the winter months.
From the foot of the mountain you can get there by shuttle bus.
The ski slopes have a total length of 45 kilometers.
According to an ancient legend, pagan gods allegedly lived on the mountaintop.
Visiting Unique Museums
There are nearly 300 museums in this country.
With just one trip, not all of them can be visited.
But at least the five most interesting of them should be paid a visit.
Among them is the Israel Museum not far from the Knesset (Parliament).
There, ancient Qumran manuscripts or Dead Sea Scrolls found in rock caves in the Judean Desert are kept, as well as about 500 thousand archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Museum of Art in Tel Aviv is also worth a visit.
There, the collection of works by the Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissaro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso will be exhibited.
In Akko you can visit the museum in Bad Al Basha, which houses several halls of ancient Turkish baths with sculptures by the visitors and bathers of that time.
In Caesarea, you should visit the unique private Ralli Museum, where you can admire sculptures of Dali and Rodin.
There are no museum guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free, and donations are generally rejected.
The fifth museum, namely the Holocaust Museum and the Holocaust Museum, respectively Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, told of one of the most harrowing chapters of the story.
The most poignant department is the monument to the children, which was built in memory of the 1.5 million children who were destroyed in the concentration camps and gas chambers.
Upon entering the room, there is complete darkness.
Stars sparkle.
And the names of the Jewish children and the countries in which they died are heard.
Ukraine is also mentioned there.
Doing something for health
Israel’s three main recreation areas are located on the shores of the Mediterranean, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
In each of the three places there are swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanariums.
Surprisingly, the Red Sea is also bathed in the winter months, as the water temperature there does not drop below 21 °C and the air warms up to 23 °C.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and bathing throughout the year.
By the way, this unusual sea with a location of 417 meters below sea level is the lowest sea in the world.
Its turquoise blue water has a high salt content and thus even non-swimmers easily carries on the surface.
The surrounding countryside is indescribably beautiful.
Visitors come here for treatments using salt water (natural salt brine) and healing mud, as well as for the treatment of skin inflammation, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes and to calm strained nerves.
Touching the secrets of antiquity
These secrets hold the old town of Tel Aviv, namely the city of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
Through this city ran the famous sea route, which connected Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The town is mentioned in ancient Greek and ancient Egyptian legends.
According to tradition, Noah built his ark here, and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda here, with which he led a long and happy life in this place.
Tourists like to stroll through the narrow streets, which are named after zodiac signs.
Fortuna is said to be, according to legend, all the hold that touch the walls in the alley with their zodiac sign.
In Jaffa, you can meet newlyweds from all over Israel and even other countries at photo shoots.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can roam the Roman theatre and conquer the fortress of the Crusaders.
In the Roman period, Caesarea was the most important city of Judea and the residence of the Roman governors, including Pontius Pilate.
In the carefully restored theatre, evening concerts and operas are performed nowadays.
Wishlist for tourists
When you go to Israel, don’t worry about your poor English skills: about 30% of Israelis speak Russian.
The money in the trip is rather not taken in any euros, but in dollars, which can be easily changed into shekels (current exchange rate: 1 dollar to 3.8 shekels).
In the city you usually make progress by bus, but in Jerusalem there is also an express tram and in Haifa the only subway line in the country with six stations that connects the lower city with the upper town.
In fact, it is an underground funicular.
A trip within the city costs 6 shekels regardless of the means of transport, which is enough including changing trains for a journey of up to 1.5 hours.
According to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated in Israel on Saturdays.
From Friday night to sunset on Saturday, markets and shops are closed, and public transport is dormant.
And on Sunday morning, the work week begins.
In many cafes, restaurants and restaurants, only kosher food is served, which excludes pork, marine products, fish without scales and food that contains both dairy and meat products.
Instead, you have the choice between different dishes with mettle and beef, soups and desserts (prepared with coconut milk), traditional Jewish humus paste, various sauces, fried balls of pureed beans and peas (falafel) as well as fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
For this, there are many well-fed cats that stray comfortably and unmolested through the streets.
In the evening you can even see them sleeping on the roofs of parked cars.
The cats like busy places and don't say no to treats.
A rental car costs between $37 per day (Hyundai Getz) and $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80) depending on the brand.
Insurance costs an additional $15 a day.
And bike rental costs 15 shekels a day.
Entrance tickets to museums cost an average of 30 shekels.
In numbers
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most of the adventurers and recreation seekers came from Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England, the USA and Ukraine.
From January to October 2012, 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists came to the Promised Land, which is an increase of 51% compared to the comparable period in 2010, before the visa requirement was lifted on 9. February 2011.
'The big and powerful' leads to Moscow: migrants save money for language
While MPs and civil rights activists discuss the benefits of the law on binding language tests for migrants, criminals are already trading fake certificates
Every year, 13 million guest workers come to Moscow, Saint Petersburg and other cities of Russia.
Most of them are the citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money for the upkeep of families remaining in the homeland.
On the 1. December came into force a law, according to which every migrant worker must take a test that certifies knowledge of the Russian language.
So far, this scheme only applies to migrants who want to work in the service sector, in the municipal housing industry and in the retail sector.
However, according to the Federal Migration Authority, the tests will become mandatory for all guest workers in the future.
It is necessary to take not only language tests, but also tests in Russian history and the basics of legislation.
Language skills must be demonstrated both for the receipt and extension of the work permit.
Exceptions apply only to citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
Also exempt from this law are persons who received their training certificates and diplomas before the disintegration of the USSR in 1991.
Meaning, problem and protection of rights
The entirety of the examination bodies will be under the aegis of the Pushkin Institute for the Russian Language, the Russian University of the Friendship of Peoples, the Moscow State University, the Saint Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
The migrants can take the tests in all cities; already more than 160 corresponding centers have already been opened in Russia.
The initiative to introduce the tests was supported by the members of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Agency.
Civil rights activists, on the other hand, asked the following question several times before the law came into force in the press: What does the whole thing actually bring?
What changes does the rule of having to have language skills bring to both the Russians and the guest workers?
Above all, counters spokespersons for the migration authority, it is about reducing the number of forced laborers.
"Many are now talking about protecting the rights of migrant workers," says the head of the Federal Migration Agency's representation in Tajikistan, Viktor Sebelev.
However, their rights must already be protected before their departure.
Only organized recruitment will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
Migrants without a job, education, language skills and medical assessment encounter problems.
Sebelev is convinced that a future migrant without language skills will inevitably encounter people with evil intentions, who put him under the pretext of help in a dark, narrow barrack, where he will endure with dozens of his equal months without food and documents and toil 12 to 14 hours a day.
We are receiving many complaints from our migrants.
"In the homeland you are promised the one thing, and on arrival you are cheated, get their passports taken and do not receive the promised wages," confirms the head of the head of the head of the labour migration department of the Tajik Migration Agency, Tolib Swaripov.
Don't scold, boss!
Nevertheless, many citizens of the Central Asian republics, who want to earn their money in Russia, admit that they not only do not master the language of the target country, but can hardly express themselves in writing in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault, but rather the evil: few Turkmen, Uzbeks and Tajiks can afford even a reasonable primary education.
Because in their families, there isn't even money to feed the children, let alone buy them decent clothes, shoes and school supplies.
As teenagers, these children immediately take the first opportunity to earn money.
"It's difficult without language skills," they admit.
“You feel humiliated and inferior.”
Civil rights activists emphasize the following important aspect regarding the law.
Only migrants with legal status have to take the test.
If you do not have this status, there is no examination and consequently no official work.
Meanwhile, the majority of guest workers continue to be in Russia illegally.
"Welcome" or "Admission prohibited for unauthorized persons"
Many migrants confirm that it is not easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason is bureaucratic hurdles and, of course, the linguistic difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
A fake registration can be made quickly and only for one and a half thousand.
The staff of the Russian police know that our documents are mostly forged and we are not registered, and from this then arises cases of blackmail.
"They want one or two hundred rubles for cigarettes and tea," the Tajik Umed Hushkadamov told journalists.
“Just don’t shy away from costs for false papers”
Already on the day the law came into force, it turned out that not only the migrants' registration documents can be fake.
Some fake certificates, which certify the completion of the language test, have already been seized by employees of the Federal Migration Agency.
The fake papers were printed with an ordinary color printer.
Of course, the new owners did not receive these for nothing: every migrant who hoped to be able to save himself the tests paid seven thousand rubles for the document.
That's more than twice as much as the cost of the official test: this one costs a migrant worker three thousand rubles.
Both public officials and civil rights activists agree that the most important immediate task is to protect the system from corruption so that the certificates cannot be bought easily.
For the moment, authorities can only promise guest workers who fall through the test the first time that they will be given time for a basic language course.
In addition, new arrivals without language skills are offered positions in areas where active communication with people is not necessary.
Interior Ministry ignores illegal arms market
Proportion of legal weapons in crime extremely low
Russia's Interior Ministry is planning a tightening of the gun law for private gun owners.
Authorities are responding to recent events: injured in shootings at weddings, as well as seven killed in the rampage of Moscow lawyer Dmitry Vinogradov.
The police want to ban the carrying of non-lethal weapons in public and raise the age for the possession of firearms from 18 to 21 years.
The proposal was supported by the chairwoman of the Duma Committee on Security and Anti-Corruption, Irina Yarovaya, and promised that the amendments to the Weapons Act will be submitted to the Duma shortly.
Not everyone is satisfied that the Russian authorities want to combat the problems by "attracting the screws."
An open letter was published on the Internet, the author of which - representatives of various arms associations - demanded from the authorities to refrain from "senseless tightening".
The percentage of crimes involving registered weapons is very small, the criminal lawyer, Vaily Lesnikov, told the BBC's Russian service.
According to the statistics of the Ministry of the Interior, 142 crimes with the application of the registered weapons were committed over the course of six months in 2012, while a total of 1.168 thousand offences were recorded for the same period.
The authors of the open letter are convinced that tightening the law for private gun owners will not stop criminals from using on the black market.
Currently, according to the authors, you can find every possible weapon for little money in Moscow.
Meanwhile, the Interior Ministry stresses that the proliferation of illegal weapons is under control.
Suppliers: from the factories to the officers
The weapons enter the black market through several channels.
There are five such main channels, recounts a former Colonel Viktor Baranez, who spent ten years in the Ministry of Education and the General Staff.
Screenshot of a web page that accepts weapons orders
The first channel is the army or the military, i.e. weapons stolen during the fighting in the Caucasus.
"The weapons were stolen by both the Russian officers and the Caucasians themselves," Baranez says.
On the second channel come illegal weapons that are stolen by criminals.
Baranez explains that this includes weapons that were stolen from the police’s armory as well as directly from law enforcement personnel.
Other illegally sold weapons come from military weapons storage facilities.
Many military camps have frequently caused explosions.
"There is evidence that some cases were arson to cover up the lack of weapons," the former military member says.
According to Baranez, the arms manufacturers also contribute to the black market.
"Today, there are countless private arms factories that cannot withstand international competition and therefore squander weapons under hand on the black market, for example in Moscow," the expert reports.
Another channel of the black market is smuggling.
Especially many pistols and rifles come from poor countries like Kyrgyzstan.
"There is a separate, sometimes craft production and a Mafia that organizes the smuggling," explains the former military member.
Where did the weapons come from?
Experts calculated what proportion of each of the five channels in the supply of illegal weapons to the black market roughly.
In 2011, a report was written by the Center for Problem Analysis and State Administration.
The experts analyzed reports from the Ministry of the Interior and the Federal Service for State Statistics, Criminological Literature and publicly available data on portals on the subject of weapons.
The vast majority of illegal weapons, according to investigators, come from the army and the legal protection authorities.
Half of all weapons on the black market are there through the "culpability of those responsible for dealing with weapons in their work," the report said.
According to the researchers, 17% of the weapons come from conflict zones, 14% are due to thefts in weapons production, and 5% come from illegal excavations.
A sales consultant for a gun shop, who does not want to be named, assures that weapons found in illegal excavations will no longer be buying anyone, as they are outdated.
According to him, it is more common for traders to get the supply in a weapons store.
