“The brain can only be moderately outsmarted so far”
The popular theme of augmented reality among followers of modern technologies has recently been perceived by the lens of special glasses.
First, Google presented a working model at its annual conference in the summer, in November it was announced that Microsoft had also applied for a corresponding patent.
In conversation with the head of the group for interactive 3D technologies at the Microsoft laboratory in Cambridge Shahram Izadi, however, it becomes clear that the glasses were only a through station for the scientists of the company.
It stimulates the possibility of manipulating virtual objects in the air with bare hands and creating virtual open spaces.
- Please briefly describe what research your group is doing.
- We deal with the interaction of man and machine, but we want to push the boundaries of this interaction.
So far, humanity has largely stuck in the phase where pixels are used on flat screens, which are sometimes touched.
However, we want to look ahead to 5-10 years and anticipate the radical changes of this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors are progressing, and nowadays no Xbox is sold without Kinect, as everyone is interested in motion control.
- What else can we expect in the future?
- Although Kinect has brought the interaction to a physical level, a lot of things still take place on the flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The input of information (the system receives more data) could be improved, the output not yet decisive.
We try to change that, working on real three-dimensional representation systems based on various technologies, including projections.
We need to release the computer world into our physical world and make it more tangible.
For this, however, it is necessary that not only the user, but also his environment is recognized.
Then we could complement the real world much more easily with virtual objects.
And first of all, we should get rid of these stupid virtual reality helmets!
- What do you think about voice control?
She's popular, but isn't she overrated?
- It is certainly not the all-purpose solution, as it raises questions about privacy, because you do not always want to inform all bystanders about their actions and intentions.
Actually, any kind of interaction with computers is good, but each in its particular niche.
For example, in the field of controlling objects in public places, we were working on a project in which we experimented with short and scarce gestures instead of expansive gestures.
The gestures were not recorded by the object camera, but by a bracelet that registered the movements of the bones and muscles.
It is still relatively large, but could theoretically be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
But overall, however, the future belongs to mixed control types, for example gestures and language.
- How?
- We'd ask you, for example, to give you this bubble box?
They say it and at the same time point to it.
- I usually just say it.
- Oh, that would be very hard to see.
- Does that mean you want the user to adapt to what a machine can and can't do at the time?
- Not necessarily, but this is about a mutual approach.
I think that in the near future we will have to work primarily on the development of new sensor types that will make it possible to capture reactions from people more accurately.
These can be laser sensors, for example, because they offer a good resolution in depth, which is very important.
- What demands do you make based on your work with the Xbox Kinect sensors on modern cameras?
Is there a lack of resolution, depth or something else?
- The present generation is basically a good starting point for our work in the field of three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, 8 megapixels with a speed of 1000 fps would not be bad.
But the main thing is not the megapixels themselves, but the quality of the matrix and the depth.
In this sense, all current technologies are not good enough for us, as the developers of the algorithms have more work.
Not only the resolution along the X and Y axes, but also along the Z axis must be taken into account.
The speed and the number of frames per second are also important.
The movements of man are extremely dynamic and frankly, the present 30 fps are too few, especially for gestures.
In our Redmond laboratory, Stephen Betishes developed a touch sensor with an adjustable processing delay of between 1 and 100 milliseconds, with today’s commercial sensors closer to the second value (60 to 100).
Not everyone understands how much this affects the interaction of man and machine.
For my work, I needed just such a device, only without touch control and with more frames per second.
- Shouldn't the number of cameras be increased?
- Kinect is currently working with three "cameras", one of which is actually an infrared transmitter and the second is a receiver for the reflected signal.
And the third camera is actually an ordinary RGB camera.
It is not used to calculate the object depth.
More cameras could potentially solve the problem...
Or amplify the problem, as more calculations would be necessary.
Nice would be a flexible, Kinect-like system, where we could play with different camera inclinations to determine how this helps us in the three-dimensional determination of a position.
- If I remember correctly, unlike Google, Microsoft did not present its glasses to the public.
Don’t you think that in terms of applying the technology of augmented reality in everyday life, glasses have the best prospects?
- Of course, it is not pleasant to always hold a smartphone in the raised hand on the go, but I think this is the best option: The most amazing variant would be a "changing" extended reality, where we could switch from the glasses to the smartphone via a cloud,
The glasses are a personal gadget and in it lies their strength (privates can only see), but at the same time their weakness, because an extended reality by means of glasses prevents you from working together with others on virtual objects.
- Let's imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holograms in the air is accessible not only Tony Stark from Iron Man, but also to normal mortals.
There is one problem that critics of this idea frequently point out: there is no tangible reaction!
The hands don't feel anything at all!
What answers does your group want to give to this objection?
In my lectures, I often talk about the fact that augmented reality is the seventh breakthrough in the interaction between man and machine.
I think the eighth breakthrough could well be the integration of the tactile perception.
An interesting method is currently the use of the second hand as a somewhat unusual projection pad.
She perceives pressure superbly!
But there are also technologies that are actually designed to give the "pictures in the air" something tangible, for example, the interference of some directed ultrasonic beams at a certain point where the finger is located creates a feeling that is currently still as weak, as if someone was blowing over the palms.
There are also ligaments for the wrist that act on the nerve endings in the fingers, even that is a potential direction.
- Have you tried to outsmart the brain?
Make it think that it feels what it should feel when it sees something?
- That's a good idea, so we haven't tried it.
Here is another task that we will have to struggle with for a long time, namely to make a person who is physically in an enclosed space believe that he is instead in an open, practically infinite space; here we work on concepts with treadmills (other than in gyms), moving platforms and large balls.
So far, the brain can only be moderately outsmarted, and there are still many busy years ahead of us.
This is precisely what makes working in the field of virtual reality so appealing to a researcher: on many topics, we are only just beginning.
