Birth in space
Earth in danger.
Global warming or collision with killer asteroid.
Caravans of spaceships with Earth's inhabitants on board are looking for a replacement planet.
To save humanity, is the important question of how we can reproduce in microgravity or on the replacement planet?
There are no many choices, in my opinion.
In fact, there are only two real planets that we could at least hypothetically inhabit.
"Namely Mars and Venus," says the research associate at the Astronomical Sternberg Institute Vladimir Surdin.
However, while the conditions on Mars are comparatively life-friendly, there is a temperature of 500 degrees on the surface of Venus.
Life would only be possible at high altitude or in the orbit of Venus, i.e. in space.
The researchers first addressed the question of reproduction in space with regard to flora.
Already half a century before, experiments with plants were carried out.
The fourth generation of the peas bred in orbit did not differ in the least from the earthly species.
This was followed by the breeding of insects, more precisely from tiny fruit flies (Drosophila), in orbit.
In 1979, quail eggs were sent into space to explore how weightlessness affects embryo development.
It's developing a normal chick.
But then the problem begins.
"The problem is that the chick has to find support; it must be able to stand on its feet and start to move," explains the head of the laboratory of the Institute for Medical-Biological Problems RAN, Vladimir Sychev.
Without a solid surface, the chicks rolled over wildly.
Ten hours later, the instincts of the newborns completely blunted off.
The chicks did not respond to light and sound.
Four days later, they simply died.
"Twice we let chicks hatch and then set the whole thing up because it's just impossible to work with them there," Vladimir Sychev notes to the failed experiment with the chicks in space.
The last incubator with animals flew into orbit 16 years ago.
The experiments will continue in the spring of 2013.
However, only same-sex species will be located on the biosatellite "Bion".
There was an experiment with rats that were already sent fertilized into space.
In principle, nothing special has been established.
"That was just with the biosatellites, but again it was just a single experiment, and the research needs to be continued," notes Vladimir Sychev.
After landing, the space rats got offspring.
The problem of reproduction directly in space could not be solved until now.
The task is difficult.
Animals that are ripped from their natural habitat simply cannot follow their reproductive drive.
Unlike animals, humans could do that in principle.
Homo sapiens is capable of abstract thinking and can create a similar emotional background.
For ethical considerations, such experiments are not carried out.
Women have been flying into space for 50 years.
The biggest risk was at Tereshkova.
The most valuable thing that humanity possesses is the female organism.
Our seagull flew away, and no one on Earth could have answered the following question: Does it survive the space flight?
Will she be able to give birth to a child after this flight?
"After all, no one answered this question," says space veteran Wachtang Watschnadze.
In June 1964, just a year after her space flight, the first female cosmonaut, Valentina Tereshkova, bore a daughter.
The child's father, Andriyan Nikolayev, was also a cosmonaut.
In 1988, the second woman in space, Svetlana Savitskaya, who was in orbit twice and even did work outside the spacecraft, gave birth to a son.
Still, a risk remains.
We have very few cosmonauts where everything went well after long flights and they had healthy offspring.
"The more, the more dangerous it is even on flights into orbit," concludes cosmonaut Valeri Polyakov, hero of the Soviet Union and hero of the Russian Federation.
And yet humanity must look for new ways in biotechnology, radiation protection and the creation of artificial gravity.
