The water represents weightlessness.
Even though adults find water to be pleasant, it is a foreign environment; yet infants perceive water as a natural element.
It is as if the little Ichtyanders bear witness to the fact that life on land descended from the ocean.
There is a link between the fact that a child is in the amniotic fluid for about 9 months in the mother's belly, and that it can then more easily get used to water.
In principle, this is logical, since from birth to the first swim only 2 weeks pass.
"That's too little time to forget something," says baby swimming instructor Marina Aksenowa.
So while for a newborn child, weightlessness is a much more natural state, the woman does not get along without gravity.
In the state of weightlessness, the abdominal and pelvic muscles regress tremendously quickly and thus the ability to squeeze the child out also decreases.
Well, let's get around this through birth-introductory aids.
The birth, for example, could also take place in a special chamber to squeeze out the child.
"But what happens then?" is the not insignificant question of Valeri Polyakov.
On the other hand, the child also needs artificial gravity.
Without feeling the earth attraction, the organism cannot form the skeleton and muscles.
A newborn child cannot be put into a stress suit like an adult in orbit for training.
He will simply lack what is of elementary importance to his life.
“This experiment, which we are doing together, namely the birth of a child in a foreign environment, will lead to the world that we will give birth to a disabled person, a completely inappropriate person,” predicts the head of the Bioethics Commission of the Institute for Medical-Biological Problems RAN, Igor Pestow.
So far, the birth of children in space is mere theory.
At some point, however, it becomes a reality when the inhabitants of the Earth in their spaceships set off to a distant planet that will become the home for their offspring born in space.
