Is there a similar authority to our NKÚ, or does the system work differently?
As far as the authorities are concerned, the German counterpart to the NKÚ is the Federal Court of Auditors, which is structured in a similar way to ours and also has a college that is merely formed somewhat differently. In principle, however, both authorities work similarly.
The competences are also comparable to a certain extent, but Germany is a federal state, i.e. that these audit offices also exist in the individual federal states - in this respect, the German system differs from ours.
The BRH may only control federal funds, which corresponds to our state resources.
Public funds managed by the districts and municipalities are subject to the control of the state accounting offices.
As for German legislation, is it easier than ours?
In general, I would be reluctant to compare this without specific information. Nevertheless, Germany is often described as a role model in some respects, although it is certainly not possible to say that Germany is better in everything.
Is it because the examiners are better?
Certainly not, but as I said: I do not like such comparisons very much.
It should also be noted that those countries that are a role model for us are also struggling with problems.
Otherwise, they would have nothing to cooperate with our authority, would they?
As for Czech legislation, what significance did the amendment of the Procurement Act have for your authority, do you already feel any impact?
In view of the fact that this amendment is only in force for a short time, it has not yet had an impact on our trials.
Since our checks take place retrospectively, a certain delay must be expected here.
So far, we are more likely to feel impact in the preparatory phase of future controls - so we have introduced the new control instrument "Recognizing risks of uneconomicality" and with this almost 14,000 public contracts - here the changes will of course have an effect, since the thresholds change, the conditions for certain types of tenders have been modified, among other things.
Do you see the passage of this law rather positively, or is the system burdened with further bureaucracy?
I think that this law is certainly a step in the right direction and hope that this assumption is confirmed.
However, the problem may arise that the rules become "stricter" and can no longer be adhered to.
Even under the previous rules, the persons subjected to an examination are accountable to the institution (for example, in the case of an operational programme of regional policy, the Regional Council) to the effect that any non-compliance with the Procurement Act is equivalent to a violation of budgetary discipline.
But does it make sense to make the law even stricter?
I don't think it's that way.
The system must exclude those who want to attack and abuse the system, and not punish those who have committed a form error that does not affect the actual decision-making.
Such a system merely puts the bureaucracy under even greater pressure.
Where's the way out of here?
First of all, let’s say which path is not expedient.
The Prime Minister recently said that the ODS did not provide the entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called. "Schwarz-Systems" would bother - what exactly does that mean?
Is the black system banned or allowed?
A law must nevertheless have its validity, and if something is prohibited by law, then the head of the government cannot simply come, and hinder the control office, whose duty is now the control of compliance with the law, in its activity.
He can say, "We change the law and allow the matter," but he can't say we're pretending to be nothing.
The Procurement Act contains relatively strict rules on the formal execution of certain processes - and that is also right for the protection of public competition.
On the other hand, however, it is also tragic if the bidder with the best offer is excluded solely due to formal errors.
The law will never be perfect, but it must be applied correctly - and that is what I think we lack.
