Šimon Ornest: At our concerts we want to gather positive energy
What do you think about the fact that the end of the world is to take place in less than a month?
This is one of those disaster reports that we humans like to jump on.
With our band The Tap Tap, we’re more fun of it and say that we’re the only band in the world that can gather enough positive energy to stop or prevent the end of the world.
In December, you will also realize a unique project with three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you introduce the project to our readers?
This is a nationwide benefit event that we have been planning for two years.
For this purpose, we want to use the marketing potential of the Mayan calendar, the end of which for the 21st. December at 11:10 a.m. is forecast.
The day before, i.e. on 20. December, three concerts will take place simultaneously from 21:00 in Prague, Brno and Ostrava.
The end of the concerts is supposed to be around the time when the Mayan calendar ends on the Pacific island of Kiribati, which is in a time zone around 12 hours ahead of us.
Who did this idea come from?
Originally from me, afterwards we designed the idea together with our graphic designer Honza Augusta.
We not only want to gather sufficient positive energy to prevent the end of the world, but we also want to think together with the public about the state in which we once hand over this world to our children.
On the occasion of the end of the Mayan calendar, we have also developed a unique collection of shoes, T-shirts, bags and keychains against the end of the world, with the purchase of which via www.e-tap.cz people can also support us.
The band The Tap Tap together with other performers also has the so-called. Hymn against the end of the world titled "Doomsday is cancelled" recorded.
The anthem on YouTube is already very popular. Will she also be heard at the benefit concerts?
Of course, and at the very end, provided that everything works out and the end of the world does not take place...
The anthem is to be sung by all performers at all three concerts at the same time.
In addition, the hymns are broadcast live together in a direct circuit by Czech television.
The text of the hymn is by Tomáš Hanák, who also plays the main character of Jesus in the video clip, also Xindl X sings with...
How did you come to work with both of them?
We also cooperate with other personalities of the Czech cultural scene, which is related to the fact that we realize many benefit events and concerts...
We strive to involve these people intensively in our projects.
It has been shown that most are interested in working with us and enjoying it.
What purpose will the proceeds of the concerts against the end of the world benefit?
For the establishment of the barrier-free educational center Studeo, where we have been working together with the association Tap at the Jedlička Institute for six years.
The students of the Jedlička Institute are regularly supervised by lecturers who help them with various leisure activities.
Since the students themselves do not have the means to visit the editors, we want to help them in this way.
Within the framework of the completion of the Jedlička Institute, a separate building is to be built, in which we will then move with this project.
At each concert, several groups and performers perform.
What criteria did you choose them by?
We wanted to put together a program that appeals to all generations including children.
In Prague, for example, Chinaski, Support Lesbian, Illustratosphere with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Jiří Suchý perform.
You can find out more on the website www.kpks.cz.
Are similar "big events" planned for the future?
In May we perform for the first time at the Prague Spring, and also for this concert we prepare an interesting program with interesting guests.
Next year we would also like to perform at the Czech House in New York, and I personally - if we are already in the USA - would also like to combine this with performances in Washington and Chicago.
Your foreign plans are not exactly small, so far you have already performed in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
However, The Tap Tap is a group made up of people with disabilities.
How do you manage these journeys logistically and organizationally?
It's not as bad as it seems at first glance.
Five of our members are wheelchair users, i.e. the wheelchairs must be transported in the luggage compartment. In addition, of course, we have to carry many instrument cases and other luggage...
Nevertheless, it has always worked out without problems, ČSA and British Airways were always very well prepared for us that I have sometimes already wondered.
Even in Moscow, where we were recently, there were no problems.
Through your trips abroad, you have a comparison of what it looks like in the individual countries with accessibility, how to deal with disabled people, etc.
How have you experienced these things so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities, where everything works better than with us, we were just in Russia witnessing that everything in the East is still in its beginnings.
Compared to Prague, Moscow is absolutely not accessible to disabled people. There, it is still unusual when someone is travelling alone in a wheelchair in the city centre.
It is not even a matter of course there that you leave a wheelchair user in the elevator, for example.
Fortunately, there are also associations that try to point out the problems of people with disabilities.
And in what way do we have to catch up with the more developed countries?
There are still a lot of things we hang in afterwards...
In addition, however, it should also be noted that an improvement in the situation always depends on the effort of those affected.
In London and Madrid, it is absolutely common for people with severe disabilities to move independently in public spaces, go to the museum, use toilets, etc.
But it is not exactly common for a larger group of disabled people to actively participate in social events, in which we are a little ahead of the West with the band The Tap Tap!
Respect in public and accessibility is one thing, but it is only when significant athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers come from our ranks that things will really start to change.
So far, these are only isolated cases of particularly strong-willed personalities.
The Tap Tap is very popular right now. But if we go back a few years, what motivated you to start a band in 1998?
At that time, I started as a supervisor at the Jedlička Institute, where I met many young people who were interested in dealing with something intensively.
And since I am a musician myself and among other things. Saxophone play, I founded a music group together with a colleague.
Well, and with time, as our moderator, Láďa Angelovič, is a little out of control (laughs).
But the band only became known in the last few years, or am I wrong?
It is true that working with well-known singers has helped us; besides, we have also started to actively promote ourselves.
We have become aware that if you do something and this cannot be seen on the outside, one’s own performance does not exist in a sense.
Thanks to EU funding, we can also afford good editors, high-quality equipment and, etc.
Was it your goal to get this far with The Tap Tap?
From the beginning, I felt the potential to approach things differently.
In show business today, one often copies the other.
This is logical in its own way, since everything new is viewed with caution and is only accepted after a long time.
There are few really unique things, and I dare say that Tap Tap is part of it.
The first impression that the viewer usually has is of course pity; this is only natural...
But this compassion is absolutely superfluous, because people with disabilities are not lonely and abandoned beings that we would have to regret.
They are people who can live and develop a full-fledged life, provided they have the necessary means to do so.
I always say that if people with disabilities succeed, this is not only progress for themselves, but for the whole society.
Was it also helpful to this success that you are a strict boss, as you hear from many people?
If you want to do something well, you are not allowed to compromise on many things and also have to demand a certain discipline.
This, in my opinion, is completely normal.
Some come to us with romantic ideas, and when they find that they have rehearsal twice a week, have to complete preparatory phases and spend a lot of time on concert tours, then the enthusiasm quickly extinguishes with many.
But that’s how it works everywhere, in every band that wants to work seriously and achieve something.
The Tap Tap currently has twenty members.
How many of them have been there from the beginning, i.e. since 1998?
Only one: Láďa Angelovič.
We are an open group. People come and go. You can't prevent that.
Those who have the will and the desire to participate are always welcome with us.
