Poland and space.
Last week, Poland was admitted to the 20th member of this space agency at a Council of Ministers meeting of the European Space Agency's member countries. Poland is thus the second member state from the former Eastern Bloc (to the Czech Republic, which was held on the 12th). November 2008 became an ESA member).
Poland began a close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated in several ESA projects in the following years.
Poland’s path into space began much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, Polish cosmos enthusiasts dealt with space travel, although they did not always understand.
I remember, for example, the lecture of A. Šternfeld of 6. December 1933 in the Warsaw Observatory, where the author presented thoughts from his pioneering work "Entrance to Cosmonautics".
The ideas of the young engineer (b. 1905), however, left the audience cold, and after years Šternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski had shown interest in his work.
Šternfeld won the Prix REP deer donated by Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch in 1934 for "Entrance to Cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became an important advocate of astronomy and space travel.
In Polish journals he published hundreds of articles and wrote several books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski’s globally recognized contribution to the development of space travel was recognized, among other things, by the fact that one of the craters on the side of the moon was named after him.
Already in 1925, a railway drain was built in Poland, for which a rocket propulsion was planned.
Unfortunately, the author of the draft and the details of this project remained unknown.
It is not even clear whether the rocket should be used to launch or brake the drain.
The information on this comes exclusively from the contemporary press.
In 1933, the Polish infantry began to deal with rocket-powered projectiles.
The research work was conducted by the Institut Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in cooperation with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzyckiegi.
It can be seen from the documents handed down that the research had reached the stage of practical testing.
The research was then interrupted by the invasion of the German Wehrmacht.
In 1937, the trade press of Ing. Rohoziński's design of a photoelectric hunting rocket on, and the following year the work "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocky was published.
Both projects dealt with the military use of rocket propulsion.
Shortly before the war, all projects for the military use of missile technology were coordinated by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Committee Doradczo-Naukowy).
The committee was established in 1937, but after two years of work its work was terminated by the beginning of the war.
Further articles on space travel appeared after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Space Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne) in the Polish press.
The first mention of this society is made in 1954 in the November issue of the magazine Problemy, in which four extensive articles are dedicated to space travel.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal to establish a space company.
At the time, the first satellite technology projects were already in place, and it was foreseeable that space exploration would have a future.
Already in its beginnings in 1956, the Polish Space Company PTA sought to join the International Federation for Space, founded in 1951, and in fact the PTA became a full member in the autumn of 1956.
The following year, the first PTA Chairman, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became Deputy Chairman of the International Federation of Space.
He held this office until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has been instrumental in the development of the highly successful meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish rocket for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, the first launch was made on the 10th. October 1958.
The rocket with a maximum altitude of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and weighed not quite 5 kg.
Later, an improved version, the RM-1A, was built, and in 1959 flight tests began in the Błędów Desert with the two-stage rocket RM-2.
The rocket was 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another stage of development should already be able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should reach an altitude of up to 14.5 km and be used for the observation of high-altitude winds.
In 1962, however, further development was discontinued.
The first rocket of the RM type was succeeded by the Meteor 1 rocket, which was developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage rocket, its total length was 510 cm and the launch weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types were developed from this rocket (Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed from each other in the size of the transport space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor 1A rocket had a transport space with a capacity of 0.4 litres, Meteor-1B over 0.34 liters and Meteor-1C over 0.62 liters.
The maximum altitude was 37 km for all three types.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor 2 rocket was developed at the aviation institute, the first flight tests of which began in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a take-off weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a payload of 10 kg to an altitude of about 60 km.
After that, the versions Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 were built.
Also worth mentioning is Poland's accession to the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960, which was followed two years later by the establishment of a national COSPAR committee.
Poland also participated in space research with Soviet satellites as part of the Intercosmos program, and in 1978 Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Czech Vladimír Remek.
