The movie Argo: When it comes to the worst, call Hollywood
In November 1979, a mob of protesting Islamist students occupied the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
For their release, they demanded the extradition of the ousted Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who had fled to the US after the revolution, who had maintained the patronage of his regime for decades.
For the American government, there was no positive way out of this situation - it could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, as this would have massively damaged the trust of its allies in other countries.
At the same time, it was unable to enforce the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution led to the establishment of a theocratic regime.
It was a major blow to the reputation of the United States, and the subsequent fiasco in the violent attempt at the hostage liberation only made things worse.
The captured diplomats were eventually released after 444 days after negotiations were brokered by the Algerian government.
The fate of the hostages provoked a wave of solidarity at home as well as anti-Iranian sentiments.
The debacle in Iran contributed significantly to Jimmy Carter's defeat to Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo by director and actor Ben Affleck describes an episode of this story that gave the US a small partial victory.
Immediately before the occupation of the embassy, six embassy staff managed to escape.
This ended after numerous complications in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
The CIA, in collaboration with the Canadian authorities, managed to bring the refugees out of Iran; in doing so, an extravagant story helped them to cover up their true identity - they traveled with Canadian passports disguised as members of a film staff who allegedly visited filming locations in the country for a science fiction film.
Combination of genres
The plan developed by the expert for "exfiltration," Tony Mendez, also made Hollywood's collaboration necessary.
In order for the camouflage to become credible, articles about this film project appeared in trade journals, press conferences were held, and the fictional production company had a real office.
The details of this operation have long been kept secret. The movie draws on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is a special combination of several movie genres.
On the one hand, it is a realistic political thriller, but at the same time a so-called one. "Caper Movie", i.e. the story of a successful hussar piece such as the film Ocean's Eleven.
As a result, the mood levels alternate in the film - on the one hand, the documentary scenes from Tehran (in the title sequence, iconic contemporary photographs are shown, and there are no major differences in the film version of the same situations either).
On the other hand, the loose passages from Hollywood, which come ironically and slightly exaggerated.
And then there are the scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions - men in suits at the meeting table, on the official hallways, on the phone...
Ben Affleck has made a remarkable reboot of his career with this film.
A ridiculed actor has become a respectable director, and even as an actor he is no longer the target of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the crime novel No Children's Game (Gone Baby Gone, 2007) and the Thriller City without mercy (2010).
At the same time, it's Affleck's first film, which doesn't set in the director's native Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of the place was among the features that set this director's previous films off from the standard of Hollywood.
However, Affleck also proves this sense in Argo, where Tehran is "played" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film play in the streets and show the reconstruction of events that have really taken place - the initial sequence of the storming of the message is very impressive in its clarity, and yet conveys the feeling of confusion and unpredictability that occurs when the story moves somewhere.
Affleck and his team also achieve a similar effect in fictional scenes (the wrong film staff at a bazaar in Tehran).
Too much action in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story does not actually offer many exciting scenes in the cinematic sense.
With the little, however, he works quite successfully, sometimes helping the reality somewhat - which then does not always seem so elegant (the scenes in which the looming crisis at the airport in Tehran is averted from a telephone call in America, or even the chase on the runway, seem somewhat artisted).
Argo's weakness is his overly broad dispersion, which is due to the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in their roles as Hollywood employees, but their characters deserve more space, and they are far from alone in the film.
Affleck's film loses some traction as a result. It is a film that you follow with some interest and the design and the one to a thriller from the 70. Years of reminiscent retro style can gout.
However, he is difficult to inspire enthusiasm.
However, as a reminder of a piece of history that is still alive in a certain way to this day and as proof of how excessive the ideas of the all-powerful and omniscient secret services are, he is sufficient.
