The MVRDV architects prove that the real adventures are not only in the mind - using the example of Spijkenisse and the recently erected Bücherberg - 2 photos
"I find the building funny, it looks futuristic, and finally there's something interesting to see again," says Lisette Verhaig, a passer-by on the side of the road.
And Stefan Spermon, IT technician in a nearby large company, says: "Yes, it's nice, the house."
But I wonder what we still need a library for today.
They all have internet, iPad and e-books.
No one goes voluntarily to one of those old-style libraries today, right?
Spijkenisse, a barely-to-sighted sleeping city just outside Rotterdam, is a strange record holder.
The 80,000-inhabitant community has the lowest education rate in the entire Netherlands.
In order to counteract this stupid circumstance, it was decided a few years ago to contribute to general education and to recreate the seven fictional bridges depicted on the Euro bills as pretty brushed reinforced concrete miniatures.
The success of the education offensive was limited.
And so the city fathers realized that there was only one way to master the statistics: A library must come here!
Winy Maas from the Rotterdam architectural firm MVRDV, master of the foolhardy bar charts and producer of witty, even often cynical buildings, took the matter with the usual serenity and appeared for competition hearing in 2003 with five books under his arm and a grin on his face.
And while the jury was still looking around him and shrugging with his armpits, the cheeky Maas stacked his exquisite souvenirs in size to a pyramid and ended his actionist-backed speech with the words: "Dear city community!"
So that's him, my suggestion for the book mountain of Spijkenisse, for the so-called Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the €30 million mountain has been piled up.
It is part of a revitalization project, which also includes underground parking, supermarket, post office and a few adjacent residential and terraced houses with a total of 50 apartments.
At the beginning of November, the Bücherberg was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
The project is also nominated for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
This makes the faceless small-town resort, which until now had no more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and a stunned ugly town hall, behind whose white facades one would be inclined to suspect a dairy factory, enriching a piece of contemporary architecture.
Above all, however, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in the history of its existence.
The Long Road to the Book
The first impression: Büchereldorado under cheese bell.
Although there is a lift that leads through the middle of the mountain massif, but the true joys of space and reading are open up when climbing the topography on foot.
The all-round glazed interior is bright and clear, the burnt clinker floor and the elegant street lights speak unmistakably the language of a public town square.
The urban environment is perfect.
You already look for park bench, dog and football-playing boys and girls.
And everywhere books, books, books.
"Normally, the bookshelves stand along the facade, and in the middle is a large, dark room that is mostly uncomfortable and impersonal," says Winy Maas.
We turned the classic room configuration upside down and put the reading area from the inside to the outside.
The interior of the Bücherberg is cleverly used: in the center are offices, Internet library, chess club, environmental center and building technology headquarters.
A special joy are the black bookcases, which are sometimes wall covering, sometimes parapet, sometimes a stirrey railing.
Optics, feel and smell are foreign.
Even diehard architects and civil engineers shake their heads at the unknown building material.
"We wanted to work with recycling materials here," explains Joop Trouborst, project manager at the municipality of Spijkenisse, at the Standard's request.
And so we came across a suitable waste product from agriculture in a Frisian farm one day.
For many years, a millimeter-thin plastic fleece has been used as a root base in the Netherlands in greenhouses and in fields.
This is cheap and time-efficient.
The thin textile lasts one or two seasons, after which it is ripe for the bulky waste.
For the library, the fleece - for the first time in these quantities - was pressed to four centimeters thick plates.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the so-called Landbouwplastic (KLP) turns into a dark, homogeneous, load-bearing material that smells a bit like new cars and a bit like sports shoe.
After 105 steps you have reached the summit.
At the end of the almost 500-meter-long hike you will not only be rewarded with a fantastic view of the city, but also with Dutch croquettes and potted ficus trees.
They provide atmosphere, but above all the right humidity in the literature mountains.
Donations for the New Soul
"You wouldn't believe it, but this house is a showcase project in terms of ecology despite the many glass surfaces," says Trouborst.
Heated and cooled with geothermal energy.
Although the Buchenberg is under a glass fall, the sun shines only briefly inside even on sunny days.
The wide wood glue binders, which stand transversely to the glass façade, serve as shading and absorb much of the sunlight.
The indoor climate is very pleasant.
The rest is done by fully automatic roller blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the initial skeptic from the IT industry, was already venturing into the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already there.
And also the TCM teacher Cynthia Bogarde, who even describes the Boekenberg as Spijkenisse's "long overdue soul".
The reason: At the opening a few weeks ago, every resident was invited to donate a book from his personal collection.
For the time being, the optical gaps in the library, which has not yet been fully stocked, are to be filled - currently 70,000 pieces.
The concept has worked.
The shelves are filled to the top.
"Nothing is worse than a half-empty library," says architect Winy Maas.
“Thanks to our invitation, every resident now has a certain relationship with this new house.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
And if it's just to the ornament.
In this way, MVRDV has succeeded in achieving the supreme discipline called identity foundation in the technical jargon.
Spijkenisse has written literary history.
As young and uneducated as she may be.
This is finally a starting point for identity.
