Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the main sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia and tripper (gonorrhea).
Common viral STIs include HIV, human pappilomaviruses, herpes genitalis, or hepatitis.
Felt lice and scabies are among the parasitic STIs.
Who are the main groups of people concerned?
Syphilis and trippers occur mainly in men who have sex with men.
The Robert Koch Institute estimates that at least four out of five of all syphilis cases reported in Germany will be transmitted through sexual contact between men.
In heterosexual adults, chlamydia infections, trichomonads, candidiasis (fungus), tripper and human pappilomaviruses are common sexually transmitted diseases.
The spread of HIV among heterosexual adults in this country is comparatively low - nevertheless: Around 20 percent of new HIV infections are accounted for by this group.
Chlamydia infections are much more common among adolescents than in other populations.
According to European surveys, three quarters of all infections affect young people between the ages of 15 and 25.
In this country, human pappilomaviruses are also common among adolescents.
How has the number of infections developed?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are reportable.
The number of syphilis infections has more than doubled from 1697 diseases in 2001 to 3698 diseases in 2011, according to the Robert Koch Institute.
The number of new HIV infections has been falling since 2007.
There were around 2700 cases in 2011.
That's about a tenth less than the year before.
What are the symptoms of senex?
The infectious diseases can cause ulcers in the genital area, discomfort during urination, discharge, subabodial pain, as well as blisters or warts.
However, they often do not cause pain or other symptoms and therefore go unnoticed.
How can you protect yourself?
Condoms can reduce the risk of infection, but do not provide one hundred percent protection.
Because in part, pathogens of sexually transmitted diseases can also be passed on through lubrication infections and close physical contact.
Therefore, experts recommend regular examinations, especially for frequently changing sex partners.
Be diagnosed early, most STIs can be cured and late effects avoided.
