Rakfisk from Norway: Is this the most foul-smelling fish in the world?
Norway's five million inhabitants enjoy one of the highest standards of living - and not only in Europe, but around the world.
Could the country's secret to success have anything to do with the local appetite for pretty foul-smelling fish?
Take a selection of overripe cheeses.
You place them in the middle of a pile of dirty, moist sportswear.
And leave them there for a week.
One has to imagine the nasal-deafening smell of Rakfisk, one of Norway’s great delicacies.
I am located in the small town of Fagernes, about three hours from Oslo.
There's snow here, spectacular landscapes - and that stubborn smell in the air that just doesn't want to disappear.
Rakfisk is trout sprinkled with salt, which - depending on how smelly you would like to have your fish - is fermented in water for up to a year.
When darkness comes across the country in Norway and the weather gets colder, Norwegians flock to a festival here in Fagernes, which is dedicated to this, well, really very captivating specialty.
"You eat it raw and then rinse it down with a glass of aquavit," says Havard Halvarsen, who actually works at the local fire station, but as a so-called "Rakfisk-General" also hosts the festival.
Around us, people eat small fish cubes and consume large amounts of alcohol.
"Candy people like the aquavit more than the rakfisk," says Havard.
The spirit can displace the smell.
I'll taste some bites.
If you avoid bringing the rakfisk near the nose, it is not bad - like sushi, which has a quite long bus ride behind it.
Rakfisk is the product of a completely different, far poorer Norwegian era, when there were no cooling possibilities and fish was soaked in airtight saltwater barrels in autumn.
In the deepest winter, he was then taken out after long fermentation and - no doubt under the help of alcohol-subdued senses - consumed.
A generation ago, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country in search of work and mostly emigrated to the United States.
Today, the population is growing rapidly - more than 13% are immigrants, attracted by a thriving labor market, high wages and comprehensive healthcare.
Even from Sweden, the old rival, which was far richer than Norway not so long ago, immigrants are flocking.
Rakfisk is seen as something important - as an essential, if strictly smelling, part of Norwegian history.
It is one of the more expensive dishes you can buy here.
But actually everything here is expensive - a small glass of beer or a sandwich costs a proud 10 euros.
Norway doesn't often make it into the world press, and most people don't seem to mind that.
Here, one still hates to call Anders Breivik by name - that racist right-wing extremist who shot 77 men, women and children last year.
Instead, one refers only to the "incident of the 22. July."
Norwegians struggle to accept that someone in their peace-loving country is capable of such brutal murders.
Mainly responsible for Norway's wealth today, growth has been one of the world's largest oil and gas industries since the early 1970s.
"But oil isn't the only reason we're doing so well," says Anna, our waitress, who distributes round trays with ripe rakfisk and embodies the Nordic ideal with her long blonde hair and stinging blue eyes.
We are a - as they say - prudent people.
Their English is spotless just like most people here.
We are not very showy, we do not like boasting.
Norway has handled its oil wealth very cautiously - a large part of the industry's revenues are invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
When, in the years leading up to the Great Depression, everyone threw money around them that they did not own, Norway kept its purse tightly closed.
"As long as we can ski in winter and go hiking in the summer, we are happy," says Anna.
"And, of course, eating rakfisk," she adds with lighthearted laughter.
I stand in the snow and line up for a different dish - I've had enough of Rakfisk.
Such a moose burger is definitely something different. The juicy meat is mouthing me.
But in the evening, the stink fish is on the menu again.
The hotel where I stay is one of several venues that organize a rakfisk dinner where guests can tune in for the best - or perhaps the smelling senses most challenging - fish.
There is a live TV circuit to a fly-clad showmaster surrounded by plates of rakfisk.
The spectacle is similar to the Eurovision Song Contest.
"What score do you have up there in the mountains for the best fish, Thor-Jürgen?"
“Here are our points, Havard.”
You clap and laugh.
A man falls from his chair, possibly overwhelmed by the aquavit.
But maybe it's the severe haze of the whole fish.
Mexico's Enrique Pena Nieto faces difficult start
While Mexico's future president, Enrique Pena Nieto, is preparing to take office, Will Grant of the BBC analyzes the challenges he faces and the mixed feelings of his people.
Traffic in Mexico City is particularly bad at the moment.
Even on better days, this is a constantly clogged city, but on Monday a ring of steel was erected, which shuts off several important traffic routes to the capital and causes chaos on the roads.
The goal, however, was not to disrupt commuters on the way to work, but to prevent protesters from reaching parliament.
On Saturday, Mexico's new president, Enrique Pena Nieto, will receive the presidential tie and take over the leadership of the nation.
He faces a complex task.
Under the outgoing government of Felipe Calderon, Mexico has proven itself well economically, but the country is in the grip of a drug war that has already cost 60,000 lives in the last six years.
"My administration is strongly committed to reducing the violence," Pena Nieto declared in the Oval Office to U.S. President Barack Obama earlier this week.
I will propose a new security strategy with which we can achieve this goal.
Before he went on an equal footing with the US president, Pena Nieto served as governor of his home state of Mexico.
In this densely populated, sprawling part of the country that surrounds the capital, opinions about the new head of state are divided.
A direct man
In the remote small town of Valle del Bravo, for example, people like to remember him.
Residents of the holiday resort attribute to him the development of tourism and the development of the infrastructure.
To reach the city, you can drive on one of the highways that Pena Nieto had built and which represent a great improvement over the fragile, bumpy roads that once existed here.
Plaques with its name also hang outside a modern sports center and an impressive interactive museum on climate change.
"We expect him to make real and lasting changes," according to his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernandez, who works as a congressman for the Pena Nieto's party, the PRI.
In particular, as far as security and the economy are concerned, we hope for an interesting and real change that our country so desperately needs.
After 81 years in power, the PRI was replaced by Vicente Fox in 2000.
Congressman Olvera admits that after 12 years outside the presidential palace of Los Pinos, the party has high expectations of Enrique Pena Nieto.
The opposition's accusations that the new president lacks substance, he rejects.
He is a very direct man, very committed and has big plans for the country.
He is an excellent statesman, but above all he is also someone who can listen.
But on the other side of the state, not many people share that view of their former governor.
In Nezahualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Neza, the contrast with the cobbled streets of Valle del Bravo could not be greater.
The place is hidden under highway overpasses and in many ways represents a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems in the community are of a crucial urban nature.
Earlier this year, the military was involved to combat the drug gangs operating in the neighborhoods, and violence against women is a particularly acute problem.
On a patch of wasteland near a large landfill, the bodies of dozens of murdered women have been left behind in the past two years alone.
During Governor Pena Nieto’s tenure, over 1,000 women were murdered in the state of Mexico – a statistic that surpasses even that of the city of Ciudad Juarez, which is notorious for its violence and the murders of innocent women.
Critics of Pena Nietos believe that he has at least not adequately tackled the problem of women's murders during his tenure.
But in the worst case, his government closed their eyes to the problem.
In a concrete building, typical of the run-down neighborhood, Irinea Buendia struggles with the tears as she shows me photos of her late daughter Mariana Luna.
According to the official version of the events, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
But her family believes she was murdered by her partner.
"When I arrived at her home, it seemed like her body had been washed," recalls Senora Buendia.
There were signs that she was beating, and the mortuary rigidity had already set in.
While her mother tells her story, a picture of Mariana looks down at us from the wall. It is attached next to a cross bearing a single word: justice.
But it is precisely these, according to the family, that they have been denied so far.
The authorities have treated me as if I was a chatterer, troublemaker, nagger.
They want their judgment to be accepted and shut up.
"But that's not possible when there have been so many formal errors and omissions," she says.
When President Pena Nieto receives the presidential tie on Saturday, he will also take on a great responsibility.
Tens of thousands of Mexican families have been affected by violent crimes over the past six years, and the new president has promised to take special care of this problem during his tenure.
"I hope as president he is the way he was as governor," says PRI Congressman Olvera in Valle del Bravo.
But this is exactly what the families of the victims in Ciudad Neza are most afraid of.
Prosecutors claim Bradley Manning did not complain about mistreatment
Prosecutors contradict Bradley Manning's allegations that he was abused in prison
The hearing deals with Manning's time at military prison in Quantico, Virginia
The defense seeks a dismissal of the charge due to harsh conditions of detention
The U.S. Army Private Man is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents
Prosecutors on Friday attempted to determine that Army private Bradley Manning - charged with the biggest revelation of confidential information in U.S. history - failed to find out several opportunities to complain about the abuse he allegedly suffered in military custody.
During a cross-examination of Manning during a pre-trial hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland explained to Maj. Ashden Fein that documents on weekly visits made by prison officials during Manning's nine-month detention in Quantico, Virginia, had no complaints about his treatment.
A day before the cross-examination, which was held as a result of a request by the defense to dismiss the prosecution - Manning had already been sufficiently punished by the harsh term of detention - Manning had testified that he had considered suicide in prison.
The U.S. Army intelligence analyst, who was arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents during his service in Iraq.
The material was then published by WikiLeaks on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed Manning as the source of the information.
In Friday's hearing, Fein went through with Manning the forms that officials had filled out after their meetings with Manning during his detention at Quantico military prison, where he had been detained under increased detention conditions from July 2010 to April 2011.
Officers asked Manning questions and wrote down his answers.
When Fein questioned him about the forms on Friday, Manning admitted that he had judged the treatment by his guards as "excellent" and the treatment by the facility overall as "very professional."
The forms, according to Fein, contained no complaints of ill-treatment, although officers had questioned Manning directly about his treatment.
Manning replied that he had expressed his concerns orally and the officials had discussed them with him and indicated that they were dealing with them. However, they were not logged.
"They wrote down (after discussing the concerns) "No problems," and that didn't necessarily mean I didn't say anything at all," according to Manning.
The judge, Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he did not complain about his treatment when he met with a committee in January 2011 to investigate the suicidal thoughts he mentioned on a form a few months earlier.
Manning responded that his intention during that meeting was to have his observational status downgraded to "prevent injuries."
The military testified that it had assigned him this restrictive status - which is one level under the threat of suicide - to his and the protection of others.
"I wanted to convince employees that I was doing well, and get rid of the observational status for the prevention of injuries (...) in order to achieve a higher quality of life in my view," Manning said.
Manning testified Thursday for his arrest and transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before he was transferred to the Quantico naval base prison in Virginia in July 2010.
He said he had considered suicide in Kuwait and had once fallen unconscious due to the heat.
Not to be allowed to know what is happening to him or in the outside world was burdensome.
"My world shrank to Camp Arafjon, on this cage together," Manning said Thursday.
I thought I was going to die in that cage.
When he was transferred to Quantico, Manning spent the majority of his days in a small cell - at least 21 hours and often more than 23 hours - and without company.
He was only allowed a mattress, a blanket, flip-flops, clothes and his glasses.
Manning said he tried to keep moving, because during the day it was forbidden to sleep or even lie down.
He always had to sleep with light, which entered his cell from the outside.
If he turned around at night and guards could no longer see his face, he was woken up to turn back.
In January 2011, Manning's lawyer formally objected to Manning's treatment.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to the military prison of Fort Leavenworth, Kansas.
On Friday, the judge also questioned Manning on an accusation he had made in his statement on Thursday - so he had to sleep one night naked in his cell in Quantico and stand naked in front of guards and other prisoners at a morning count.
Manning had testified that he had never had the opportunity to envelop himself with his blanket during this count.
At the questioning on Friday, Manning stated that he had concluded from an order of his guard that he should drop the ceiling he could have covered with. However, he admitted that no one had asked him to do so.
On Thursday, Manning had testified that he was forced to sleep naked the previous night. He would have previously tried to show an official that he was not a threat to himself.
Manning had told the official that he could have used the waistband of his underpants or his flip-flops to hurt himself, but did not.
That night, Manning testified, his underpants, flip-flops and glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account his prison experiences and drastically reduce his degree of detention should he be convicted at his trial in the military court. This is scheduled for early next year.
The defense has indicated that Manning will plead guilty to lesser offenses, while other charges deemed too extreme are to be challenged.
The continuation of the hearing is scheduled for this weekend. The prosecution is expected to justify the conditions of detention.
The Pentagon is sticking to its position that Manning has been detained in accordance with the provisions that apply to all detainees held in Quantico under the highest security precautions.
Charges against Manning include favoring the enemy, unlawful publication of intelligence on the Internet, transmitting national defense information, and stealing public property or documents.
If he is found guilty on all charges, he faces a life sentence.
My Mexican-American identity crisis.
Many people are forced to leave Mexico due to the lack of opportunities
Mexicans tend to blame the emigrants - they call them hard times in memory, he says
Navarrette believes Mexican Americans are caught between two worlds
On a recent trip to Mexico City, I had only just crossed the hall and had arrived at passport control when perplexity spread in me.
Signs referred to two queues: One for "Mexicanos" ("Mexicans"), another for "Extranjeros" ("Foreigners").
I stood there for a few seconds, unsure which I should go to.
I grew up in Central California and have been called "Mexican" all my life.
An ethnic abbreviation - just as my friends in Boston call themselves "Irish" or my friends in New York "Italians."
Later, I decided to go for "Mexican-American."
But this was Mexico.
And in my grandfather's home, there was no need for abbreviations or hyphens.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish, at least good enough to assert myself in this language at both ends of an interview.
But I don't have the vocabulary of a native speaker, and I can't get rid of my American accent either.
So I took my American passport and put myself in line for Extranjeros.
I was thinking about that moment this week when future Mexican President Enrique Pena Nieto visited the White House to meet with President Obama.
On the agenda were all those issues that one expects when the minds of these two countries meet: immigration, drugs and trade.
Pena Nieto was also very interested in talking about the growth of the Mexican economy. It is one reason why Mexicans are just as likely to remain in Mexico today, rather than emigrate to the United States.
He wants to ally himself with the United States and Canada and create a North American trade bloc modeled on the European Union.
And Pena Nieto vowed to continue Mexico's war against the drug cartels, even if he did not give specifics in this regard.
Mexico's relationship with the United States is complicated and full of resentment.
Most Americans probably never waste a single thought that the United States invaded Mexico in 1848, forcing the country's leadership under gunpoint to leave them more than half of their territory.
But for Mexicans who think in centuries rather than minutes, memories of this event are not to be overlooked.
So once a U.S. government official makes even mildest criticism of Mexico, one hears - in the Mexican press and among the country's elites - complaints about how Americans are harassing the sovereignty of their neighboring country.
And the children of Montezuma embark on the warpath.
And yet Mexico's biggest challenge, in truth, lies in the relationship with the more than 35 million Mexican Americans living in the United States.
Want to talk about resentment?
There's more than enough.
Mexico has winners and losers. people for whom the country offers opportunities, and others for whom it does not.
The only reason so many people of Mexican origin live in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio is that at one point in our family tree, a person - perhaps a parent or grandparent - didn't get a chance in Mexico and migrated north.
And in most cases, this person corresponded to a profile - dark-skinned, uneducated, from a poor village, etc.
We are the descendants of these people, and our faithfulness is to them.
Not Mexico.
And although we may now have lived the American dream, attended good schools and received good jobs, we must never lose sight of it that it is the American dream we are living - not the Mexican one.
Our identity may sometimes be blurry, but as far as our loyalty is concerned, this is not the case.
This clearly applies to the United States.
What's more, we are aware that many members of the Mexican leadership class don't like us.
This is based on mutuality.
They see us as a memorial of a humiliating defeat and look down on us because we are not Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough, our ties to Mexico will never be strong enough.
In their opinion, our existence is a symbol of failure.
If our families hadn't failed in Mexico, they wouldn't have left.
And then we wouldn't see ourselves trapped behind the silk curtain now - with a pleasant life in the United States, but somehow lost.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and legally immigrated to the United States as a child, reminds me that there are tensions between Mexicans and Mexican Americans because Mexicans have a clearer idea of who they are - and Mexican Americans resent it.
While she is a U.S. citizen, she sees herself as part of two countries.
Yet many Mexican Americans I know feel they do not belong either to the other.
We love the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but also Bruce Springsteen.
You enjoy the best of both worlds, but none of them are rooted in.
In Mexico, we are seen as Americans.
And in the United States, we are seen as Mexicans.
As I should learn during my trip, there's something that makes this relationship even more complicated: some Mexican leaders and parts of the educational middle class want to resume their ties to the diaspora.
They want to use Mexican Americans as provisional "ambassadors" for Mexico who represent their interests in the United States.
We are to tell our American colleagues about how great a visit to this country is and put pressure on the political leadership to intensify their ties with Mexico.
Well.
This isn't gonna happen.
Too many hurt feelings.
And given the unfair distribution of income, unbridled corruption and drug violence, many of us are not so sure whether it is really a great country.
I'm afraid you'll have to go through it alone, Amigos.
That's fair.
If at least some Mexicans are not yet willing to forgive the United States for dealing with Mexico a century and a half ago, they must also accept that some Mexican Americans hold a grudge for how their family members were treated not so long ago.
Hmmm.
Maybe we're more "Mexican" than I thought.
Old battles, new Middle East
The ceasefire between Israel and Hamas could prove to be an unexpected cornerstone for peace
Can there ever be lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
The latest bloody events seem to nip such hope in the bud.
In the midst of the usual admissions of guilt, countless buildings have been laid to rubble, more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis killed - and for the first time, rockets from Gaza have been smashed near the Israeli metropolis of Tel Aviv and the holy city of Jerusalem.
Yet although Israelis and Palestinians seem trapped in their historic conflict, the Middle East is changing around them.
The Arab Spring has created a new, uncertain situation, and whether they want it or not - Palestinians and Israelis have become part of this turmoil.
Perhaps this will just lead to more bloodshed.
Yet there are reasons to believe that the deadly stalemate could finally come to an end.
A war that is neither lost nor won
At first glance, optimism seems anything but appropriate given the current situation.
Even if the one on 21. Ceasefire agreed in November continues, this week's fighting has strengthened the hardened on both sides.
The leaders of Hamas, the Islamist movement that has controlled the Gaza Strip since 2007, will claim to have pushed back the Israelis, even though his group itself has suffered large losses.
Although several Hamas leaders are killed and the 1.7 million Gazans are crammed into one of the most desolate and densely populated corners of the planet, Israel has so far failed to destroy Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is gaining ground in the West Bank, which is controlled by the rival, moderate Palestinian group Fatah.
And Hamas leaders could conclude that they have time on their side.
Just as Islamists have gained influence in the Arab world, Hamas has been able to draw powerful and rich friends to their side.
Turkey, a resurgent, regional power once considered Israel's closest Muslim ally, has taken sides for Hamas - just like Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic Gulf states.
Cheering Hamas supporters believe an Islamist crescent is forming around Israel - from Lebanon in the north, where militant Hezbollah has power, via Syria, where rebels of an increasingly Islamist imprint could face the fall of Bashar Assad, to Jordan, where Hamas allies threaten the king.
And in particular, the rise of the Muslim Brotherhood under President Muhammad Morsi in Egypt - by far the most populous and most important Arab country - on the southern flank of Israel has permanently changed the balance of the region.
Hosni Mubarak, the secular despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his 2011 overthrow, had little time left for Hamas.
In contrast, the Brotherhood is in-laws with Hamas and its leaders are more dependent on popular views.
In future diplomatic negotiations, Hamas could prove to be an actor that cannot be pushed out even by Israel and the United States.
The Israeli hardliners, on the other hand, allow an opposite conclusion to be drawn.
Militaryly, Hamas is no longer a threat.
The Israeli missile defense system, "Iron Dome," has proven itself and many of the Hamas missiles have been destroyed.
At least for a while, Israel will be able to sleep more soundly.
In diplomatic terms, the United States is steadfastly holding on to its position. Many European countries have blamed Hamas for the latest escalations of violence.
Israel has fared well in recent years, particularly under Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu, who has largely ignored the peace process.
Although rockets from the Gaza Strip have killed about 30 Israelis since 2004, the country has remained relatively free of suicide bombers - not least thanks to the barrier facilities that run into the West Bank and thus into the bulk of a possible Palestinian state. These protect the Jewish settlements, which have been declared contrary to international law, but are being expanded ever further.
Netanyahu is well off. His Likud party has turned out in the run-up to the elections on 22. January under Avigdor Lieberman allied with an even more combative group.
Why even these deceitful Palestinians coddle and leave them a state of their own?
If they were indeed in control of the West Bank, would they not fire rockets just like their fellow Gazans?
No, it's better to keep them in check behind the wall and punish them should they dare to raise their heads.
Maybe the hardliners will be able to prevail. Yet the Arab Spring could put a dash through the bill for them.
Even if the Islamists, who are now in power in Egypt and in other countries, have little left for Israel, they will initially focus on the difficulties in their own country.
The defense budget of Israel is larger than that of its four Arab neighbors combined.
A war with the local superpower will hardly help the new Arab governments to repair their economy.
That pragmatic President Morsi teamed up with Barack Obama to reach a ceasefire could be an auspicious sign - and perhaps symbolize the beginning of a new era.
Israelis should also think more long-term.
While the rest of the Arab world is taking tentative steps toward democratization, Palestinians continue to be deprived of their right of self-determination - a powder keg that will undoubtedly one day explode in the Israeli-occupied territories, just as a bus exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
The oppression is already undermining democracy in the Jewish state, and with the growth of the Arab population, this situation will only worsen.
Bloody missions to push back Hamas in the Gaza Strip will increasingly take their diplomatic toll over the years.
Both sides need an impetus from the outside
The correct answer is the one represented by the more reasonable representatives of both sides, the bulk of the rest of the world, and by this newspaper: two states where Israel is ceding territories for security purposes.
The hope, which is small for the near future, is that the ceasefire will grant outsiders more influence to enforce this solution.
Egypt, together with Turkey and Qatar, must now stop arms shipments in the Gaza Strip and is better positioned than ever before to convince Hamas of the idea of a Jewish state based on the 1967 borders, supplemented by territorial swaps and a common Jerusalem.
Outside Arab nations should also persuade Hamas and Fatah to reach an agreement.
This would do more for the creation of a Palestinian state than with the upcoming request for UN observer status.
Obama, too, must do his part to persuade Israel to negotiate.
During his first term, he missed the notion of his own peace plan.
Far away in the White House, it seems as if he was also averse to involvement.
But that is a regrettable, short-sighted perspective.
The United States has a significant interest in a stable Middle East.
This includes a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
Australian laws on uniform cigarette packaging come into effect
Health warnings and diseased body parts on neutral green packs that are the same for all tobacco brands
The world’s first laws on uniform cigarette and tobacco packaging have come into force in Australia. This replaces brand logos and colors with neutral, olive green lids, which are also printed with drastic images showing sick body parts and infants and children suffering from cigarette smoke.
Apart from the different health warnings and pictures, the only difference between the packs in the brand names, which are printed in identical, small font, is from next Saturday.
Australia is thus introducing the world’s strictest regulations for tobacco packaging.
The Australian federal government wants to dissuade young people from smoking by eliminating the glamorous picture of tobacco use.
The government is proceeding from studies that have shown that people who have not yet started smoking at 26 will probably not start smoking even after that.
"You can see from children of young age that they understand the message that tobacco companies are trying to promote with their brand image," said Federal Minister of Health Tanya Plibersek. She cites studies that have shown, for example, that children associate the crown of a logo with the idea of a princess.
Although Australia has one of the lowest smoking rates in the world and the changes will have only a minor impact on the profits of multinational corporations, other countries are already considering similar steps.
The tobacco lobby fought hard against the laws.
The laws would favour black market trade, which would lead to cheaper and more accessible cigarettes.
"The laws will lead to serious, unintended consequences," says Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco Australia.
Chinese and Indonesian counterfeiters will offer far larger quantities of these products on the roads of Australia.
Others, on the other hand, say the laws have boosted their business.
Sandra Ha of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family business, notes that the demand for cigarette cases and silicone lids to cover the unbearable packaging has increased enormously since the corporations failed the British American Tobacco, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco two months ago at the top Australian court with their contestation of the laws.
Zico has sold up to 6,000 units to wholesale business and is waiting for new holdings.
For us, this is a good deal.
According to experts, the catch is in the popularity of social media with exactly the population to which the plan is addressed.
A number of Australian laws have banned tobacco companies from TV advertising, prohibiting them from acting as sports sponsors and forcing most traders to stop laying out cigarettes in stores. Now tobacco advertising has moved to the Internet.
The Australian government has banned internet advertising by local businesses and sites, but has no influence on international sites.
