In a constantly electrified world, it's nice to be bored
This Thanksgiving I unexpectedly spent five hours in the airport when our plane fell out due to mechanical problems and we had to wait for another plane.
So I had enough time to worry about boredom.
I don't want to lie.
Waiting half a day at the airport for a flight is quite annoying - even when books, magazines and iPhones (and, of course, tax-free shopping) are available.
But more and more academics and child development experts are citing boredom as something positive.
When it comes to them, it's okay for us - and our children - to be bored occasionally.
This forces the brain to get lost in interesting thought processes, which may promote creativity.
And because most of us nowadays are almost constantly staring at one or the other screen, the benefits of boredom no longer benefit us.
Should we welcome boredom with open arms?
Yeah.
And no.
I'll come back to that again.
Like many people, I have always assumed that boredom is a relatively current phenomenon that has developed with increasing free time.
Yet Peter Toohey, professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary in Canada and author of "Boredom: A Lively History" (Yale University Press, 2011) doesn't see it that way.
"In fact, boredom has a very long history," he says.
Pompeii's house walls adorn a Latin graffiti over boredom that dates back to the first century.
And then there is the question of how we actually define boredom.
John D. According to Eastwood, an associate professor of psychology at the University of York in Ontario, Canada, the problem is that boredom has been defined and discussed in many ways.
After a long reading of research literature and the presentation of the idea to a focus group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues came to the conclusion that boredom can be defined as the experience of "wanting to pursue a satisfactory activity, but not being able to do so."
Boredom differs from apathy in that the person is not busy, but wants to be.
In the case of apathy, however, there is no urge to do anything.
The key experience of boredom, he says, consists in a "disturbance of the attention process, coupled with a bad mood and the feeling that time is only slowly passing."
Boredom can sound almost like depression.
But Professor Eastwood believes, though these two states might be related, bored individuals see the problem in their environment or the world, while depressed individuals see the problem in themselves.
Sometimes we think we're bored, even if we're just struggling to concentrate.
In their study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention" - in English, for example: "The Idle Mind: The Definition of Boredom from the Aspect of Attention," which appeared in September in the journal "Perspectives on Psychological Science," Professor Eastwood and his colleagues point to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a volume on which a person read a magazine article.
Some groups heard a loud television program from the neighboring room that had nothing to do with the content. Others heard it at low volume, so it was barely perceptible, while the third group did not hear these sounds at all.
The people who heard the barely audible television said they felt more boredom than the other two groups - they had trouble concentrating, could find no reason for these and attributed their difficulties to boredom.
Trying to focus on a difficult or exhausting task can lead to boredom, disturbing attention can lead to boredom, says Mark J. Fenske, associate professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the authors of the study.
If, on the other hand, one performs a monotonous activity - "just like the search for faulty products on a factory conveyor belt, music can distract and help not to feel bored".
In fact, he says, we now know that fidgeting and scribbling, often interpreted as a sign of boredom, can even combat them by staying physically more attentive to people.
"Studies have shown that children who are allowed to stomp around learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to sit still," according to Professor Fenske.
We all get bored at some point - my late flight, a booming loudspeaker, a particularly tiring movie.
But some people are more easily bored than others.
To measure these differences, researchers developed a "scale to boredom vulnerability" in the 1980s.
On the scale are statements like "A lot of things I have to do, repeat themselves and are monotonous" and "I have so many interests that I don't have enough time for everything."
Using such scales, researchers have found that boys become boring more often than girls, according to Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida - especially as far as the need for more and a greater variety of external stimuli is concerned.
But in general, teenagers are a pretty tight-knit heap.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of human and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted nearly 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day with a pager.
He found that 32% of adolescents at school and doing homework were bored, while 23% said they were bored when they were not at school.
Yet only 3% of parents said they felt bored.
Professor Larson says today, 21 years later, that he does not know whether the percentages in terms of boredom have increased or decreased.
However, he is sure that "the youth is perceived as particularly boring", mainly because children and teenagers do not have a big influence on their everyday life.
So back to my original question: Is boredom healthy?
Sometimes not, because in extreme cases, it causes people to take extreme physical risks and fall into gambling or drugs to alleviate them - this is what studies have shown.
On the other hand, many philosophers and authors examine the relationship between boredom and creativity. This is the opinion of Professor Vodanovich, who has been researching the subject for more than two decades.
"With boredom, the brain wants to tell you that you should do something different," said Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at the University of New York.
But the brain doesn't always know what to do best right now.
When you’re bored and you use that energy to play guitar and cook, you’ll be happy.
But television can create feelings of happiness in the short term, but these evaporate in the long term.
So if you give your bored child an iPad, you can dissuade it from boredom. However, it has not learned to entertain or control itself, says Professor Fenske.
And he adds: "Self-control is transferred from one situation to the other".
The child not only learns to converse, but also receives more self-control in other areas.
I don't think we should celebrate boredom.
We shouldn't see them too critical either.
Instead, our goal should be to feel comfortable even beyond the constant activity and technology sprinkling.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
“It sounds like we have to be bored more often. But boredom is the excruciating, unceasing desire to do something meaningful," he says.
He believes that in truth people are only looking for a way to switch off and relax.
“In an environment where we are constantly overstimulated, it is difficult to get busy when the noise is once silenced.”
There is no clear guideline for the new marijuana law in Colorado
