Petronella Wyatt: I was bullied from Oxford because I'm Tory
Not only university students of today are being attacked for their views
It has always been my biggest dream to get a place at Oxford University.
Both my father and my older brother had attended the university that I once considered to be the greatest temple of knowledge in the world, for a modern Greek symposium that promoted the great pillars of civilization - free thinking and tolerance.
But within two weeks of my entry into Worscester College at the end of the eighties - where I had planned to study history - I had packed my suitcases again and thus brought about the first scandal of my life.
My father collapsed in tears.
My friends were confused.
In the Evening Standard, it was said that I had left because I would have had a problem with fellow students having sex in the neighbouring room.
The author A N Wilson mischievously explained that I had left university because I was forced to drink from damaged cups.
The truth, however, was less amusing.
I ran away.
Yes, ran, because I suffered from systematic bullying and threats.
Not because of my rather unusual name, or because I had come from a private school.
I had only been harassed for one reason - a reason that seemed all the more narrow-minded and cruel in this alleged cradle of enlightenment: my now-deceased father, Woodrow Wyatt, had been a key adviser to Margaret Thatcher and I supporter of the Conservative Party.
Why am I mentioning this right now?
Well, according to current reports, a new generation of students of moderate rights are suffering from similar persecution.
The organized and rising hatred of Tory students at Oxford, meanwhile, has developed such dimensions that a group of them last week called for equal protections for equality that benefits gays, disabled people and ethnic minorities.
Conservative members of Corpus Christi College's Junior Common Room (JCR) say they are "often actively isolated, personally attacked and declared undesirable because of their political views."
They are calling for a place on their college's equality committee to ensure that their opinions can be freely expressed.
Her situation was worsened by a recently broadcast documentary about political students on BBC Two, "Wonderland: Young, Bright and on the Right," which portrayed Tories as an eccentric and neo-Nazi.
It featured, among other things, graduate Joe Cooke, former president of the University of Oxford's conservative student association, who drove in a Rolls-Royce and flaunted with a silver-coloured suit and silver-studded walking stick.
At other universities, conservative students say they are considered "scapegoats for the introduction of higher tuition fees."
The 20-year-old Luke Black, vice president of the Conservative Student Association of the University of Nottingham, said in a Sunday newspaper: "There is a growing left-wing tendency at universities.
People think we’re like the Bullingdon Club without even getting to know each other.”
Samuel Roberts, 21 and history student in Corpus Christi, who initiated the request for greater protection, is of the view that such a climate is "unpleasant." 19-year-old Stephanie Cherill, president-designate of Oxford's conservative student association, says she has observed a growing rejection among JCR members towards students of the moderate right.
"This poses a danger to the intellectual discourse and to the well-being of members," she says.
In my first weeks at Oxford, I belonged to such a minority.
As an incredibly shy 18-year-old, I had arrived in September 1986.
The hatred of the Conservative Party had reached its peak.
The previous year, the university had voted not to award an honorary title to Margaret Thatcher - a former student - due to cuts in higher education.
The atmosphere would have even made Stalinists startle.
In the first days of the first-year week, during which new students get to know each other and the tutors, I got a taste of the future events.
I had the experience that the tutors not only tolerated the mocking of Tory students, but even participated with joy.
Political issues such as the miners' strike, privatization and the government's rejection of sanctions against South Africa's apartheid regime found their way into the wood-panelled rooms of the tutorial.
At my first of these events, I should have French texts from the 18th. Translate century into English. I had not been prepared for what was to come.
"Miss Wyatt," said the tutor Harry Pitt (now deceased), "please translate the first paragraph."
I stumbled in the process.
Pitt was a little man with a face like made of cake dough, and quite hateful.
"Do Thatcher supporters refuse to learn French, or are they just stupid?" he asked me.
The other students giggled.
In my eyes, tears were pouring out.
"I suggest that they take a few French lessons in your free time - so if you're not too busy with your social activities," Pitt growled at me.
I returned to my room with my head hanging.
That night, I was sitting alone in college at dinner when someone tipped me lightly on the shoulder.
It was a second-year English student named James who introduced himself as a member of the conservative student association.
"I know who you are," he said kindly.
Unfortunately, it is as it is.
Anyone suspected of being Tory is being harassed.
It's bad enough for me, but they know your father is close to Margaret Thatcher, so it's going to be worse for you.
Most Tory freshmen pretend to be supporters of the Labour Party.
At a local pub, I later tried to pretend.
I insisted that I not on all points with Mrs. Thatcher agreed.
This trick should prove unsuccessful.
A freshman in philosophy, politics and economics, who had ironically attended the Eton College, considered conservative, said to me, "You are the daughter of a fascist pig".
You're polluted.
Other students shared his opinion.
I was perverted and dirty.
"How do Tories have sex?" one asked me.
They're beating each other, right?
I felt the way homosexuals must have felt before the more liberal legislation of the United States.
Would I ever succeed in living a normal life at Oxford University?
Would I not be able to meet like-minded people until after dark?
Should I have to turn to the Labour Party and suppress my natural inclinations?
The three years that lay before me stretched before my spiritual eye to a purgatory of ostracism and isolation.
The only tutor who openly revealed himself as a Tory was Norman Stone, a professor of contemporary history, who was based in my college.
He was hated not only for being a conservative, but also because he had advised Thatcher on foreign policy and written speeches for them.
He was rarely there.
He hated the place, found it provincial and petty, and rejected it for his Marxist-determinist historical perspective.
In 1997 he accepted a professorship at the University of Bilkent in Ankara, Turkey.
"You're not going to be happy here," he told me.
I began to commute between Oxford and my parents' house and found refuge with more open-minded friends and family members in the city.
I told my father that I hated Oxford, and why I did it.
He seemed incredulous.
During his time in the 1940s, all political views were accepted.
"But it's the best place in the world," he said, small-minded.
They would never do something like that, not in my city of dreaming towers.
Even my communist friends always displayed impeccable manners.
His damp eyes clouded.
Give it a chance.
I'm sure they're just teasing you.
It would break my heart if you left.
Exhausted by my frequent travels to London, my emotional resistance became weaker.
One of my male friends, also A Tory supporter, had given in to the pressure and renounced his convictions.
During a tutorial the following week, where another history tutor had seriously claimed that I was "an enemy of the people," I decided to do the same.
Although I secretly fell apart from shame, I admitted that my parents had subjected me to a "brainwashing," calling them "old suckers."
The relief only lasted briefly.
It was my father who slapped the last nail into the coffin of my Oxford career.
At the time, he wrote two columns a week in the Murdoch press.
My door was locked.
I hid in my room, and after five minutes my bunnies gave up.
When they left, I packed a suitcase and took the first train to London.
I never returned.
You are welcome to call me a whiny slack.
But no 18-year-old should ever have to suffer from such intimidation and malice in an educational institution.
And even more tragic is that it was Oxford - a university that not only produced 14 Tory prime ministers, but still hides behind an undeserved reputation of equality and freedom of thought to this day.
