The world's most difficult profession: the human work animals of Kawah Ijen
For four euros, the bearers of the Indonesian volcano put their lives and health at risk when they carry 70 kilos of sulfur over the steep, rocky paths.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others work literally in hell.
This is the case with Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn their lives by getting sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano to the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, he must descend every day to the bottom of his crater, where the sulphur-containing gas flowing out of the earth solidifies in contact with the air.
After breaking out large sulphur stones that can weigh up to 70 kilos in total, he transports them in two bamboo baskets on his shoulders across the sloping paths of stone.
While it is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to a height of 2386 meters, the exhausted wearers need more than 40 minutes for the ascent at the turtle pace, while they must maintain balance and carefully set their steps so that they do not slip and crash.
They know that every step can cost their lives, as happened to a French tourist who crashed years ago on the steep slopes of the Kawah Ijen.
Kawah Ijen's miners earn 5 eurocents for every kilo of sulfur they mine.
Arriving at the top, they make their way between the tourists, who photograph them like circus monkeys and walk with the tiringly heavy baskets three kilometers to the scale, which a mining company has set up a little further down at an altitude of 1850 meters
The society is PT Candi Ngrimbi, which has been exploiting the deposits in the volcano and (never better so) its workers, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 eurocents) for every kilo of sulfur.
This is then sold for 10,000 rupees (83 euro cents) each to the petrochemical industry, because this mineral is widely used in everyday life and is used for the production of matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even for bleaching sugar.
"Since we normally carry 70 kg, we receive about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each route," Anto explains to us, who usually does three routes a day.
For each route he needs three hours, after which he is completely done, but at the end of the day he has 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) together.
What looks like a miserable wage for such an almost inhuman effort, however, is three times what he would earn with the field work.
"The daily wage of the miners here, where 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) are paid per day during the coffee harvest and the average monthly income is two million rupees (167 euros), is very high," explains the carrier, who previously worked as a bricklayer on the tourist island of Bali.
There he earned 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day, and the work was not so hard, but Anto has returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a village nearby, and that for a reason that is as important in Indonesia as much as the sulfur: "I married a girl from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I have taken them to Java to convert them to Islam".
Anto has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs frequently and his eyes are irritated because of the toxic gases.
The 27-year-old Anto has been putting his life at Kawah Ijen at risk for three years, whose sulphur has already left his first traces, although he covers his face with a mask and special glasses.
Anto has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs frequently and his eyes are irritated because of the toxic gases from the volcano.
This is the price he has to pay for reaching his dream.
"I'm going to work here for another two years because I want to open a shop or learn Spanish or French," he promises in a more than acceptable English.
This sympathetic and intelligent, but punished by life, young man could work as a tourist guide, waiter or at the reception of a hotel, but instead he does the work of a carrier.
He shares a dirty wooden hut with other wearers and gets up at two o'clock every morning, because the sulfur also flows out at night, where its characteristic yellow color shines bluish in the dark.
The shadows challenging, he climbs into the crater in the light of a small headlamp on his helmet, which he bought from his own money.
About 400 straps load on the crater floor the baskets with sulfur on their shoulders.
Despite its large profits, the mining company has not mechanized sulfur mining to save costs, and does not provide any equipment to the carriers, who work on their own account and are paid by weight.
They also receive no share of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) surcharge per camera, which the guardians of this natural park, together with the entrance fee of 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros), require from the tourists who come to photograph the volcano and the human carrying.
"This work is for the animals and not for humans," protests Madrusin, a stocky, 42-year-old carrier who has worked at Kawah Ijen for three decades since leaving school.
He is able to carry up to 110 kg and assures that he will continue "as long as possible" because he needs the money to educate his three children between the ages of 10 and 18.
I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano has been my whole life.
Even if the sulfur burns the throat and the eyes itch, when the wind suddenly turns and the miners clamp in the thick columns that rise from the crater, the men are so hard that no one complains of serious illnesses ... of course, except for the usual breathing problems, osteoarthritis, pain in the knees and blisters on the shoulders that have deformed from the weight of the baskets.
With the basket on his back, Unainik is only able to carry 50 kg at the age of 53.
Every day, he and his companions break 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which are transported by three trucks via a goat path between the bushes to the camp in Tamansari at a distance of 18 kilometers.
"I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano has been my whole life," explains Unainik, opening his mouth wide, in which some teeth are missing.
Of his five children, the oldest at the age of 30 also works as a sulfur carrier.
Time passes, but poverty persists generation on generation in one of the toughest professions in the world: that of those who work as human burdens at the Kawah Ijen.
