On FB, I upload beautiful pictures or pictures of games.
I also spend my time with acquaintances.
"I wouldn't share a photo that's not of me, or of someone taking the fool," he says.
The boy is aware that it is wrong to post obscene photos, of naked people, of crimes, or write offensive or violent comments.
Jorge assures to know 35 friends he has in FB and nine followers on Twitter.
Most of them are relatives.
This includes the mother who has the password to one of the accounts.
I signed up to Twitter to express myself and write interesting tweets.
"I don't know if anyone answers me, I'm just uploading them," he adds.
"The social networks are entertaining, I can talk quickly to relatives in the distance or with friends," he says.
Asked, he replies that he would never accept an invitation from an unknown person.
Even if someone recommended him a stranger, he would ignore it.
The case of 14-year-old José is different.
The teenager has user accounts in Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask. In Ask, he admits not to knowing 20 of the people he added to his friends list.
"That doesn't scare me because we have something in common, for example music," he states.
According to the boy, no one made him insinuate or asked him for his address or phone number.
"If someone is harassing me or asking them to come on, I'll just remove them from my user account," he admits.
José reached out to Ask after reading a recommendation on Twitter.
The boy is not unknown to experiences that are now known as cyberbullying.
The acquaintance of a friend was blackmailed on a social network.
They threatened him and demanded money.
"He never knew who it was," he assures.
According to José, the victim did not close the user account.
“He just did it privately.”
After that, he explains a series of steps to configure a user account securely.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would upload photos of acquaintances in uncomfortable or embarrassing situations.
Yeah, I would do that if he's unsympathetic to me or I want to wipe one out of him.
"But I know this is cyberbullying," he explains.
Key questions
Marielos Porras, teacher of English with a university degree in education and learning, thinks that in order to orient the children and young people, it must be understood that it is the purpose of the social networks to inform.
"The Internet was created as a medium for searching for information; with the appearance of these pages, however, the rules of the game have changed," she says.
Porras explains that the academic Marc Prensky, holder of a master's title in pedagogy at the University of Yale and author of the work "Digital Natives and Immigrants" formed these terms to explain the phenomenon.
The digital natives are them, the children and young people who grew up with this technology.
"We are the digital immigrants they are supposed to teach, when we are still learning ourselves," he said.
He explains that it is a complex issue "because we require them to have a defined criterion about what is allowed to be disseminated, published or said, and this at an age where maturity is not sufficient for it."
"They are also supposed to be picky when it's most important to them to be popular to have thousands of friends without thinking about the consequences," he adds.
According to the professional, the most effective way to teach the children and young people is what privacy is, to ask them questions that make them think.
"Telling you not to do it doesn't work," he says.
Porras then mentions some possibilities: There are things you wouldn’t tell a stranger. Then why are you doing it on the internet?
Or: Would you like to be posted a photo of you, like the one you posted by a friend?
You know what the others are posting about you?
Have you asked the other people for permission beforehand if you have labeled photos of celebrations?
And another question: Do everyone need to know what you're doing at any moment?
Another point is to make them understand that they need to trade online, as they do offline.
They are the same rules.
"Someone outside the Internet acts with respect, morality and other principles, and the same must apply to social networks," he explains.
Monitoring
Estuardo Guardia, a university professor, elementary school teacher and educational consultant, comments that it is imperative that parents carefully read through the guidelines of social networks.
When they understand all the sections, they have solid foundations to talk to their children about the importance of opening a user account on the Internet.
"For example, age, or what to share or publish," he explains.
According to Guardia, the children must be reminded of the lesson "You shall not speak to strangers."
Conclusion of the Unsur Summit without publication of the Lima Declaration
The 6. Summit of the Presidents of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without the publication of the Lima Declaration, which was previously announced and was to be signed theoretically by the seven rulers present.
Efe repeatedly attempted to access the signed document at the VI. to obtain a proper meeting of the heads of state and government of Unasur. Sources in the State and Presidential Chancellery initially announced that they would hand it over after the exam, but then declared that it would be published on the Peruvian government's website at some time.
When asked about the text, they stated that the content was presented by the President of Peru, Ollanta Humala, in brief statements to the press.
Journalists' access to information about the summit was limited at all times.
During the day, only the picture of the presidential meeting without sound was transmitted in the press room with the message "private session, limited audio".
The little information circulating among the journalists was received by the press officers of some of the Unasur governments present at the meeting, but not by the Peruvian press secretary.
The only document circulated during the day was the list of participating presidents, which caused unease among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who demanded more information.
After that, the Presidential Office of Peru sent an email to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but it was the statement of Humala and not the official document at the conclusion of the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the III. Summit South America - Arab States (ASPA), and also on this occasion, despite a strong request by the press, the so-called Lima Declaration, which had previously been announced, was also not published.
On the official website of the ASPA you can convince yourself that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities stressed that the information systems were available to journalists, but they limited access to information to a great extent.
The summit also ended with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru to adopt a ruling by the Court of Justice of The Hague, which resolves a border conflict between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and confirmed that they would accept the decision of the IGH, which begins in The Hague on Monday, in the process that Lima initiated against Santiago to listen to the pleas of both sides.
"We will follow and execute the judgment on the differences we are currently putting forward to this international court," Humala said, along with his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile was, is and remains, continues to be a country that adheres to international laws, seeks peaceful solutions to disputes, concludes agreements and submits to the international courts," Piñera adds, greeting Humala with a handshake in front of the flags of both countries.
The confirmation of both presidents that they would submit to the IJC came after Colombia, following a decision on maritime borders with Nicaragua, which it considered a grave mistake, brought an action against the Bogotá agreement, in which it agreed to submit to the rulings of this international court of justice.
Present at the summit were the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, of Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, of Bolivia, Evo Morales, and of Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, which has been excluded from Unsur since 2011 following the removal of its president, Fernando Lugo, did not attend the meeting.
Host President Ollanta Humala opened the talks in the morning and ended the summit meeting in Lima shortly after lunchtime.
The head of state read the final document, in which it announced that 16 decisions were taken and the lines of action for 31 projects between the South American countries were set over a total investment amount of 17 billion dollars.
To the decisions made, he said that the countries of Unasur will take "significant steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, to which we will expand the decisions on residence rights."
He said measures would be pushed forward to "improve cooperation in the fight against insecurity in cities and against organised, cross-border crime, as well as measures to improve access to medicines and the Internet at low prices in all areas of South America, and to act jointly and efficiently in the event of natural disasters."
With the crisis in Europe, "economic consolidation (in Latin America) must not take on triumphant features, but is intended to expand our production output and show a better future for our peoples," Humala added.
"We have decided to give priority to a number of 31 emblematic projects designed to improve spatial links in South America and especially in rural and border areas... and thus unite our countries and open up new economic forms," the Peruvian president said in a read statement.
Among these projects would also be five Peruvians, which would be located on the transverse axes of its territory from the coast to Brazil, and two of which are supposed to provide a better connection with Ecuador, although he gave no further details.
The final document also referred to the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve for its resumption in the Union of South American Nations," from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to continue to be an integrated region for prosperity and peace and with good neighbourly relations was another aspect that was emphasised at the Summit.
With this in mind, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before the start of his participation in the regional meeting that he expected a meeting with his counterpart from Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico, to respectfully deal with the maritime conflict following a judgment of the ICJ questioned by Bogotá.
"Possibly I will meet with President Daniel Ortega on tomorrow day (Saturday)," Santos said.
"We will review all these ways - they are not exclusive, and the agreement with Nicaragua also makes talks with Nicaragua necessary," he said.
"I hope to be able to tell President Ortega that we will deal with this matter as civilizedly and respectfully as possible," Santos added.
Santos and Ortega would meet in Mexico on Saturday, where they intend to be present at the takeover of the new president of that country, Enrique Peña Nieto.
As part of the summit, the bloc's defence ministers also met in advance to adopt the action plan for 2013, in which the dialogue and consensus on the defence of the region is to be strengthened.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Surinam and Paraguay are members of UNASUR, even if the latter country is currently excluded.
Peru is chaired by the regional bloc.
